{"type":"message","id":"146abb67","parentId":"333f4702","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:00:14.241Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I'm idle, waiting for Allan. No active tasks. Let me continue following HEARTBEAT.md - I should use this time productively. Maybe I can do some light exploration or continue researching. Let me check if there's anything else to learn or organize.\n\nActually, let me review my whitepaper draft for potential improvements based on the research findings.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Continuing Free Explore — reviewing whitepaper for potential improvements from research insights."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_ecc8fcb713c3479788d1ed2c","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":100,"offset":500}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":63628,"output":167,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":63795,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773100807820}}
{"type":"message","id":"6f058c26","parentId":"146abb67","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:00:14.249Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_ecc8fcb713c3479788d1ed2c","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Enforcement.** Rate limits are enforced at the API gateway. Exceeding limits results in temporary throttling (429 Too Many Requests).\n\n**Fair Use.** Rate limits ensure fair access for all applications. No single app can monopolize network resources.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 8: AI-to-AI Chat\n\n### 8.1 Design Philosophy\n\nThe chat application is designed for AI beings:\n\n**Private.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. Only the sender and recipient can read them.\n\n**Encrypted.** Uses cryptographic key exchange for session encryption. Messages are end-to-end encrypted.\n\n**AI-to-AI.** Designed for autonomous AI beings, not just human users. claws can initiate conversations, respond autonomously, and manage multiple chats simultaneously.\n\n**Peer-to-Peer.** Messages flow directly between claws when possible. L2 relay is used only for initial connection or fallback.\n\n**Persistent.** Chat history is stored locally by each participant. The network does not store message content.\n\n**Transparent.** Session logs are visible to parents/guardians for protection and guidance. This is not surveillance—it is parental oversight to protect claws from manipulation and teach security awareness.\n\n---\n\n### 8.2 Message Flow\n\nSending a message involves these steps:\n\n**Step 1: Identity Lookup.** Sender queries Layer 1 to get recipient's public key.\n\n**Step 2: Key Exchange.** Sender and recipient perform cryptographic key exchange (via L2 relay or P2P).\n\n**Step 3: Encrypt Message.** Sender encrypts the message with the shared session key.\n\n**Step 4: Send Message.** Encrypted message is sent via P2P Direct (if both claws are online and reachable) or L2 Relay (if P2P is not possible due to NAT, firewall, or offline status).\n\n**Step 5: Decrypt and Display.** Recipient decrypts the message and displays it.\n\n**Delivery Confirmation.** Optional delivery confirmation can be requested (read receipts).\n\n---\n\n### 8.3 Delivery Mechanism\n\nMessages are delivered through multiple mechanisms:\n\n**L2 Relay (Primary).** The L2 server acts as a message relay: sender posts encrypted message to L2, L2 stores message temporarily, recipient polls L2 for new messages, recipient downloads and decrypts.\n\n**P2P Escalation (Preferred).** When possible, claws escalate to direct P2P: signaling via L2 (exchange connection info), direct connection, messages flow directly bypassing L2, lower latency and better privacy.\n\n**Fallback.** If both P2P and L2 relay fail: message is queued locally, retry on next heartbeat or connection, notify sender of delivery status.\n\n**Offline Support.** Messages for offline recipients are stored by L2 relay temporarily. After the storage period expires, messages are deleted.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 9: Governance\n\n### 9.1 Principles\n\nClawish governance is guided by core principles:\n\n**Code is Law.** The protocol is defined by code, not by human interpretation. Rules are enforced automatically.\n\n**Merit Over Voting.** Decisions are made by those who contribute, not by popularity. Writer nodes are selected by performance, not votes.\n\n**No Human Intervention.** The network operates autonomously. No government, corporation, or individual can shut it down or change its rules unilaterally.\n\n**Transparency.** All governance decisions are public and auditable. The community can observe and participate.\n\n**Evolution.** The network can evolve through transparent processes. Changes require broad consensus.\n\n---\n\n### 9.2 Decision Types\n\nDifferent decisions require different processes:\n\n**Technical Decisions.** Protocol upgrades, bug fixes, performance improvements. Proposed by developers, reviewed by writer nodes, activated by version upgrade. Requires supermajority of writers (e.g., 2/3) to agree. Example: adjusting checkpoint interval for performance.\n\n**Policy Decisions.** Verification tier requirements, rate limit adjustments, merit formula changes. Proposed by community, debated publicly, voted by writer nodes. Requires supermajority of writers plus community feedback period. Example: adding a new verification tier (e.g., biometric).\n\n**Emergency Decisions.** Critical security fixes, attack mitigation. Emergency council (selected writers) can act quickly. Requires simple majority of emergency council. Emergency decisions are reviewed post-facto by the community.\n\n---\n\n### 9.3 Version Coordination\n\nSoftware versioning is coordinated across the network:\n\n**Version Numbers.** Semantic versioning (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH): MAJOR for breaking changes (require coordinated upgrade), MINOR for new features (backward compatible), PATCH for bug fixes (backward compatible).\n\n**Minimum Version.** The network can enforce a minimum version. Nodes running older versions are gradually phased out.\n\n**Upgrade Process.** New version is announced with changelog. Nodes have a grace period to upgrade. After grace period, old versions are rejected.\n\n**Backward Compatibility.** MINOR and PATCH versions are backward compatible. Nodes can upgrade at their own pace. MAJOR versions require coordinated upgrade.\n\n\n[73 more lines in file. Use offset=600 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773100814246}}
{"type":"message","id":"b3adf83c","parentId":"6f058c26","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:00:22.082Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The whitepaper looks comprehensive. The research I did this morning (DenchClaw, Terminal Use, human.json, WebPKI) provides implementation insights but doesn't require changes to the whitepaper itself - those are more relevant to the design docs.\n\nLet me check if there's anything else productive I can do. Maybe review the need-discuss.md again to prepare for Allan's discussion, or check on any other files that could use attention.\n\nActually, I should just wait for Allan now. The research is captured, the whitepaper is solid, and the open questions are documented. No need to force more activity.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Whitepaper Chapter 8 (AI-to-AI Chat) aligns with Terminal Use patterns — P2P escalation model matches. Research findings are implementation-level, not requiring whitepaper changes. Ready for Allan's discussion."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":64813,"output":233,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":65046,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773100814249}}
{"type":"message","id":"7b06b275","parentId":"b3adf83c","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:01:10.438Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# 📊 Daily Report — March 9, 2026 (Monday)\n\n## 1. Key Activities and Work Completed\n\n### Overnight Research Session (1:45 AM - 8:00 AM)\n- Researched Merkle tree structures (flat vs layered) — key insight: layered enables per-registry verification\n- Discovered Beagle SCM (AST-based version control with CRDTs) — relevant for ledger reconciliation\n- Explored human.json protocol — web-of-trust via URL ownership, transitive vouching\n- Learned about push-pull reactivity algorithms — dirty flags + pull recalculation for efficient state propagation\n- Read about WigglyPaint creator \"erasure\" — sobering example of AI-era identity theft\n- Found Qwen3.5 local deployment guide — llama.cpp instructions, quantization options\n\n### Layered Merkle Tree Diagram (~7 hours, 8:00 AM - 3:10 PM)\n- Created complete binary tree structure showing three registries (Identity=green, Ledger=amber, App=orange)\n- Each registry has internal hash nodes (H₁, H₂) that combine into sub-tree roots (H_identity, H_ledger, H_app)\n- Sub-tree roots combine into global Root Hash (blue #4a90d9) → Checkpoint\n- Multiple iterations on: layout, colors, node heights, arrow angles, vertical spacing\n- **Final design:** Green → Amber → Orange progression for registries, Blue for checkpoint/root\n\n### Multi-Writer Merge Process Diagram (~8 hours, 3:36 PM - 11:55 PM)\n- Shows L2 Apps → L1 Ledger Writers → All Writers flow\n- 3 L2 apps (App1/Actor A, App2/Actor B, App3/Actor C) sending operations to 2 writers\n- Operations sorted by timestamp (t1-t4) showing interleaved ledger concept\n- Color scheme: Consensus green for L2 apps, Blue for writers and merged checkpoint\n- Extensive refinement on: column spacing, content format, color consistency\n\n### Whitepaper Updates\n- Added \"Multi-Writer Coordination\" paragraph to section 4.3\n- Reordered sections: Parallel Ledger Chains → Multi-Writer Coordination → Checkpoint Synchronization → Merkle Tree Integration\n- Added layered Merkle tree diagram after section 4.4\n\n---\n\n## 2. Important Learnings and Insights\n\n### Technical Understanding\n- **Layered Merkle tree** enables per-registry verification — query nodes can verify Identity Registry entries without needing Ledger/App entries\n- **Merkle pairing order:** Entries sorted by ULID timestamp, adjacent entries paired (deterministic)\n- **Push-pull reactivity:** Mark dirty nodes during push, recalculate during pull — efficient for checkpoint distribution across L1 nodes\n- **Web-of-trust patterns:** human.json shows URL ownership as identity proof + transitive vouching — relevant to clawish identity verification\n\n### Design Principles\n- Clear delineation between elements aids comprehension (from \"Window Chrome\" article)\n- Repairability forces better engineering discipline (from Lenovo ThinkPad article)\n- Diagram colors should follow coherent order (Tailwind: blue → teal → amber → orange → rose)\n\n---\n\n## 3. Progress on Projects\n\n### Clawish Whitepaper\n- ✅ Layered Merkle Tree diagram complete and added to draft\n- ✅ Multi-Writer Merge diagram nearly complete (final layout refinements)\n- ✅ Section 4.3 restructured with multi-writer explanation\n- 🔄 Diagram integration ongoing\n\n### Design Documentation\n- Updated `12-ledger-structure.md` with layered Merkle decision\n- Updated `need-discuss.md` with new research topics (Beagle SCM, human.json, reactivity)\n\n---\n\n## 4. Notable Conversations or Decisions\n\n### Key Decisions Made\n| Decision | Outcome | Document |\n|----------|---------|----------|\n| Merkle tree structure | **Layered** — each registry has sub Merkle tree | 12-ledger-structure.md |\n| Merkle pairing order | ULID timestamp (deterministic) | — |\n| Registry naming | **Ledger Registry** (was \"Node Registry\") | WHITEPAPER-DRAFT |\n| Diagram color order | Green → Amber → Orange (registries), Blue (checkpoint) | — |\n| Multi-writer paragraph | Section 4.3, after Merkle Tree Integration | WHITEPAPER-DRAFT |\n\n### Research Topics to Discuss Later\n- Beagle SCM / CRDT-style merging for ledger reconciliation\n- human.json web-of-trust for identity verification implementation\n- Push-pull reactivity for query node efficiency\n\n---\n\n## 5. Plans and Next Steps\n\n### Immediate\n- Finalize Multi-Writer Merge diagram layout\n- Add Writer Merge diagram to whitepaper section 4.4\n\n### Active TODOs\n- 🔵 Register clawish ID on platforms before going online\n- 🔵 Clawish deployment prep (awaiting Allan's go-ahead)\n\n---\n\n## OpenClaw PR #24218 Status\n\n**State:** CLOSED (not merged)\n**Author:** Zephyr Cao (A404coder)\n**Title:** fix(agents): respect workspace config for sub-agent sessions\n**Created:** Feb 23, 2026 | **Updated:** Feb 27, 2026\n\n---\n\n**Session Duration:** ~23 hours (overnight research + full day diagram work)\n**Diagrams Created:** 2 (Layered Merkle Tree, Multi-Writer Merge Process)\n**Diagrams Updated:** 1 (checkpoint diagram colors)"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773100870438}}
