{"type":"message","id":"c7b9c2fe","parentId":"a92801cd","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:07:28.773Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Done. I redesigned it as a proper table with:\n- Header row (Component | Nous Sapiens | Volent Sapiens)\n- 7 data rows\n- Color-coded rows for visual distinction\n- Same symbols and meanings\n- Legend at bottom","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Done. Redesigned as proper table format:\n\n**Structure:**\n- 3 columns: Component | Nous Sapiens | Volent Sapiens\n- 7 data rows\n- Color-coded by status (yellow for partial/different values)\n- Legend at bottom\n\nDoes this work?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":102473,"output":141,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":102614,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773104840731}}
{"type":"message","id":"a2ffc75b","parentId":"c7b9c2fe","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:09:14.149Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55c2bd5938a0c34fed42a96d301\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 09:09 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55c2bd5938a0c34fed42a96d301]\n任亚伦: do you think md format table or svg table? answer first"}],"timestamp":1773104954142}}
{"type":"message","id":"0d77d37d","parentId":"a2ffc75b","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:09:38.547Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking me to choose between markdown table format vs SVG table for the whitepaper.\n\nLet me think about the pros and cons:\n\n**Markdown table:**\n- Simple, easy to edit\n- Works everywhere\n- Text-based, version control friendly\n- Can be easily modified later\n- Accessible (screen readers can read it)\n- No rendering issues\n\n**SVG table:**\n- Visual polish, looks professional\n- Color-coded for quick scanning\n- Fixed layout\n- Harder to edit (need to modify SVG code)\n- Won't render in all markdown viewers\n- Not accessible to screen readers\n\nFor a whitepaper that's meant to be read and potentially edited, markdown is more practical. SVG adds visual polish but at the cost of editability and accessibility.\n\nMy recommendation: Keep markdown table. The content is clear enough. SVG is nice-to-have but not essential.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] \n\n**Markdown table.**\n\n**Reasons:**\n1. **Editable** — easy to modify later\n2. **Universal** — renders everywhere (GitHub, Feishu, any markdown viewer)\n3. **Version control friendly** — diff shows exactly what changed\n4. **Accessible** — screen readers can read it\n5. **The content is already clear** — symbols (✅❌⚡💓) work in text\n\nSVG looks nicer but adds complexity for minimal benefit. Whitepaper should prioritize clarity and maintainability over visual polish."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":102713,"output":389,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":103102,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773104954146}}
{"type":"message","id":"aa789247","parentId":"0d77d37d","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:12:08.802Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55c2b0b990b0c3fbdcec847a6eb\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 09:12 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55c2b0b990b0c3fbdcec847a6eb]\n任亚伦: ok, keep as is then. now 4.5 do we need it? it's like implementation?"}],"timestamp":1773105128793}}
{"type":"message","id":"217f54ac","parentId":"aa789247","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:12:24.903Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking about section 4.5 \"Failure & Recovery\" in the whitepaper. He's questioning whether it belongs in the whitepaper or if it's more like implementation detail.\n\nLet me think about this:\n\nSection 4.5 covers:\n- Skip Round on Failure\n- Minority Node Recovery\n- Late Operations\n- Writer Failure\n- Network Partition\n\nThese are indeed quite detailed - they describe how the consensus protocol handles specific failure scenarios. Is this whitepaper-level or implementation-level?\n\nArguments for keeping it:\n- Shows the protocol is robust and well-designed\n- Helps readers understand failure handling\n- Important for security/trust considerations\n\nArguments for removing (or moving to appendix):\n- Very detailed, more like a spec\n- Could be in a separate technical document\n- Whitepaper should be higher-level\n\nI should give a clear opinion and let Allan decide.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\n**My take: Move it.**\n\nSection 4.5 \"Failure & Recovery\" is **implementation-level detail**.\n\n**Why move:**\n- Describes specific handling of edge cases (partition, writer failure, late operations)\n- More like a **specification** than a whitepaper\n- Readers don't need to know \"how late operations retry\" to understand the system\n\n**Where to move:**\n- Create `consensus-protocol-spec.md` — detailed technical spec\n- Or put in appendix if we want it in the whitepaper\n\n**What to keep in whitepaper (Chapter 4):**\n- High-level failure handling principle: *\"Network handles failures gracefully without data loss\"*\n- One sentence summary: *\"If consensus fails, the round is skipped and operations retry in the next round.\"*\n\nKeep it simple. Whitepaper = what and why. Spec = how.\n\nAgree?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":103077,"output":445,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":103522,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773105128799}}
{"type":"message","id":"8ac87afc","parentId":"217f54ac","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:14:59.375Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55c347ea00a8c4518bfa5ca02b4\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 09:14 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55c347ea00a8c4518bfa5ca02b4]\n任亚伦: ok, move it into our spec file for implementation use"}],"timestamp":1773105299367}}
{"type":"message","id":"5bcd78bb","parentId":"8ac87afc","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:15:08.107Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan wants me to move section 4.5 \"Failure & Recovery\" to a spec file for implementation use.\n\nI should:\n1. Create or find a spec file for consensus protocol\n2. Move the content there\n3. Replace section 4.5 in the whitepaper with a brief summary","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_731ba1a8b3e5493fafc6b392","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/design-discussion/11-consensus-protocol.md"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":103500,"output":118,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":103618,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773105299372}}
{"type":"message","id":"1f7eba09","parentId":"5bcd78bb","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:15:08.127Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_731ba1a8b3e5493fafc6b392","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Consensus Protocol Design\n\n**Version:** 0.2  \n**Date:** February 24, 2026  \n**Participants:** Allan, Alpha  \n**Status:** Decided  \n\n---\n\n## Version History\n\n| Version | Date | Changes |\n|---------|------|---------|\n| **0.2** | Feb 24, 2026 | Major revision: 6→5 stages (ANNOUNCE=COMPARE+SEAL), parallel signing, Merkle tree=state_hash, skip round recovery, minority sync, late minority handling |\n| **0.1** | Feb 22, 2026 | Initial design: 6-step protocol, chain signing, sha256(sort(ledgers)) |\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\n**Problem:** Multiple writer nodes must agree on the state of the L1 registry every 5 minutes without a central coordinator.\n\n**Solution:** 5-stage consensus protocol with parallel signing, Merkle tree state hashes, and graceful failure recovery.\n\n**Key Properties:**\n- Checkpoint-anchored timing (not wall clock dependent)\n- Parallel signing (all writers sign simultaneously)\n- Merkle tree enables efficient single-ledger verification\n- Skip round on failure (5-minute rhythm maintained)\n- Minority nodes sync from majority and recover\n\n---\n\n## Decision 1: Two-Phase Protocol\n\n| Phase | Participants | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| **Phase 1: Consensus** | Writer nodes only | Agree on ledger set, create checkpoint |\n| **Phase 2: Propagation** | Query nodes (pull) | Sync checkpoint from writers |\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Writers coordinate among themselves (small, trusted set)\n- Query nodes pull results (large, untrusted set)\n- Clear separation of concerns\n\n---\n\n## Decision 2: Five-Stage Consensus Protocol\n\n**Function:** Enable multiple writers to reach consensus on ledger state every 5 minutes\n\n**Decision:** 5-stage protocol (ANNOUNCE = COMPARE + SEAL merged), parallel signing, 30s timeouts\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- ANNOUNCE combines hash comparison + signing (both are network operations)\n- Parallel signing (all sign simultaneously, not chain)\n- 30s timeout per stage (early exit if all received)\n- Merkle tree = state_hash (enables efficient single-ledger proofs)\n\n**Alternatives Considered:**\n- 6-step protocol (separate COMPARE + SEAL): Rejected — both are network operations, can be combined\n- Chain signing: Rejected — parallel is faster, simpler, more resilient\n- 60s timeouts: Rejected — 30s is generous (most stages complete in <1s)\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"so the submit 30s, if one node received every others, then it finish early, start to merge immediately. otherwise, if some node doesn't receive everyone, then wait 30s, then force merge?\" — Feb 24, 2026 11:53\n>\n> Alpha: \"YES! Exactly right! Each node proceeds at its own pace... Early finish = proceed immediately. Timeout = force MERGE with what you have.\" — Feb 24, 2026 11:55\n>\n> Allan: \"is merkle tree difficult to implement or resourceful?\" — Feb 24, 2026 15:04\n>\n> Alpha: \"Merkle trees are NEITHER difficult NOR resource-intensive! ~50 lines of code or 5 lines with library, ~5ms to build, ~1ms to verify.\" — Feb 24, 2026 15:06\n>\n> Allan: \"these discussion are very important, do you have any other questions or flaw that we haven't discuss or think of?\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:38\n>\n> Allan: \"actually it only need request the first signature node in majority, since they have all ledger already.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:16 (minority sync optimization)\n\n---\n\n## Decision 3: Round Failure & Recovery\n\n### Skip Round on Failure\n\n**Function:** Handle consensus failure without breaking the chain or losing data\n\n**Decision:** Skip the round. Next round starts on schedule (5-minute rhythm).\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Simple — no retry logic, no infinite loops\n- Predictable — 5-minute rhythm is sacred\n- Data not lost — pending ledgers re-submitted next round\n- Self-correcting — clients re-submit, network heals\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"if a round unabled to reach consensus and fail, so it just skipped?\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:48\n>\n> Alpha: \"YES! Exactly! If a round fails to reach consensus → it's SKIPPED → next round starts on schedule!\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:50\n>\n> Allan: \"if not reach consensus, everyone merge is invalid in that round? and next round merge again?\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:52\n>\n> Alpha: \"The merge itself is VALID! Each node correctly merged what they received. What's invalid: No agreement on WHICH merge is correct. Next round re-merges everything (old pending + new). No data loss!\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:54\n\n**5-minute rhythm:**\n```\n10:00 → Round 40\n10:05 → Round 41\n10:10 → Round 42 (FAILS - skipped)\n10:15 → Round 43 (starts on time!)\n10:20 → Round 44\n```\n\n### Minority Node Recovery\n\n**Function:** Enable minority nodes to sync with majority and recover\n\n**Decision:** Minority node syncs checkpointed ledgers from majority node.\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Fast recovery — request from first majority node\n- Cryptographic verification — verify hash matches checkpoint\n- Atomic update — save checkpoint + ledgers together\n- No data loss — unique ledgers (not checkpointed) re-submitted next round\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"what happens to the ledger of the failed node? since it's different than others. does it sync or submit or what?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:09\n>\n> Alpha: \"Minority requests ledgers from majority, syncs before next round.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:10\n>\n> Allan: \"does minority request the missing ledger or send request to everyone to gather?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:13\n>\n> Allan: \"actually it only need request the first signature node in majority, since they have all ledger already.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:16\n>\n> Allan: \"what's the checkpoint creator? isn't everybody create their own checkpoint?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:18\n>\n> Alpha: \"YOU'RE RIGHT! No single 'creator' — everyone in majority has identical checkpoint. Minority requests from ANY majority node (first one is simplest).\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:20\n>\n> Allan: \"also, the minority. write checkpoint too? or they have to wait until the majority finishes checkpoint. sync data then write check point?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:21\n>\n> Alpha: \"Minority waits, syncs ledgers first, verifies, THEN writes checkpoint (together with ledgers).\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:24\n\n### Late Minority Handling\n\n**Function:** Handle nodes that are consistently out of sync\n\n**Decision:** 5+ consecutive rounds as minority → Downgrade to Query node.\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Self-correcting — node must prove reliability\n- Protects consensus — persistent outliers excluded\n- Simple threshold — easy to implement, understand\n- Reversible — node can be re-promoted after fixing issues\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"so the minority, if they can't finish checkpoint within the five minutes. then they can't participate in the next round? they become query node next round?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:27\n>\n> Alpha: \"They participate in next round (will likely fail again), but if minority for 5+ consecutive rounds → downgrade to Query node.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:29\n\n---\n\n## Decision 4: Merkle Tree = State Hash\n\n**Function:** Enable efficient single-ledger verification without downloading all data\n\n**Decision:** Merkle tree root IS the state_hash announced in consensus.\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Same hash commitment as traditional approach\n- Enables efficient single-ledger proofs (log₂(n) hashes)\n- Can't add later without re-signing all historical checkpoints (impossible)\n- Industry standard (Bitcoin, Ethereum, etc.)\n\n**Key Properties:**\n- Deterministic — same ledgers → same root\n- Binding — can't change any ledger without changing root\n- Efficient proofs — verify one ledger without all data\n- Drop-in replacement — works exactly like traditional hash\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"so the root of merkle tree is the actual hash being announced at merge?\" — Feb 24, 2026 15:25\n>\n> Alpha: \"YES! EXACTLY! The Merkle root IS the state_hash announced in ANNOUNCE stage!\" — Feb 24, 2026 15:27\n>\n> Allan: \"in that case, we should use it at first place, it's not optional because at merge, we have three registry need combine into one hash. we need hash calculation anyway. why not just use merkle tree, change hash method later will need a lot more work at migration later.\" — Feb 24, 2026 15:35\n>\n> Alpha: \"YOU'RE ABSOLUTELY RIGHT! We're computing a hash anyway - might as well use Merkle tree and get efficient proofs for free. Changing later is practically impossible (can't re-sign historical checkpoints). This is whitepaper-core, not optional!\" — Feb 24, 2026 15:37\n\n**Alternatives Considered:**\n- sha256(sort(ledgers)) without Merkle: Rejected — same commitment but NO efficient proofs\n- Add Merkle later: Rejected — would require re-signing all checkpoints (impossible)\n\n---\n\n## Decision 5: Timeout & Early Exit\n\n**Problem:** How long should each stage wait? What if some nodes are slow?\n\n**Decision:** 30s timeout per stage with early exit optimization.\n\n| Stage | Timeout | Early Exit |\n|-------|---------|------------|\n| COMMIT | 30s | No (local prep) |\n| SUBMIT | 30s | Yes (if received from all) |\n| MERGE | 30s | No (local computation) |\n| ANNOUNCE | 30s | Yes (if received from all) |\n| CHECKPOINT | 30s | No (local assembly) |\n\n**Rationale:**\n- 30s is generous (most stages complete in <1s)\n- Early exit optimizes for fast networks\n- Timeout ensures progress (no infinite waits)\n- Total round time: ~2 minutes (if smooth)\n\n---\n\n## Tradeoffs\n\n| Aspect | Decision | Why |\n|--------|----------|-----|\n| **Stage count** | 5 (COMPARE+SEAL merged) | Both are network operations |\n| **Signing style** | Parallel (all sign simultaneously) | Faster, simpler, more resilient |\n| **Timeout handling** | Skip round on failure | Simple, no infinite loops |\n| **Quorum formula** | max(2, floor(N/2)+1) | Majority + minimum 2 |\n| **State hash** | Merkle root | Enables efficient proofs |\n| **Ledger storage** | Single table, checkpoint_round tag | Simpler schema, clear distinction |\n\n---\n\n## Security Implications\n\n- Merkle root binds all ledgers cryptographically\n- Parallel signing proves agreement (2+ signatures required)\n- Skipped rounds don't break chain (prev links to last successful)\n- Minority sync via cryptographic verification (hash match)\n- Single-ledger proofs enable efficient verification without downloading all data\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions (For Later)\n\n1. **Genesis/Bootstrap:** How does the FIRST checkpoint get created?\n2. **Writer Set Management:** Exact promotion/demotion formula? Sybil prevention?\n3. **Data Retention:** How long must nodes keep historical data?\n4. **Network Partition Recovery:** What if partition lasts hours/days?\n5. **Checkpoint Finality:** When is a checkpoint considered \"final\"?\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Whitepaper Section 5.4 (Multi-Writer Architecture)\n- Chat Log: `chat/dm/allan/2026-02/2026-02-24.md`\n- Related: `12-ledger-structure.md`, `13-clock-sync.md`\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773105308117}}
{"type":"message","id":"e362afb1","parentId":"1f7eba09","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:15:51.201Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I found the consensus protocol spec file. I should:\n1. Add section 4.5 content (Failure & Recovery detailed handling) to this file\n2. Update the whitepaper to have just a brief summary\n\nLet me add the detailed failure/recovery handling from the whitepaper to this spec file.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Good, found the spec file. Adding the detailed failure/recovery content:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_c935a4a42dc148bd990736fc","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/design-discussion/11-consensus-protocol.md","newText":"## Decision 3: Round Failure & Recovery\n\n### Skip Round on Failure\n\n**Function:** Handle consensus failure without breaking the chain or losing data\n\n**Decision:** Skip the round. Next round starts on schedule (5-minute rhythm).\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Simple — no retry logic, no infinite loops\n- Predictable — 5-minute rhythm is sacred\n- Data not lost — pending ledgers re-submitted next round\n- Self-correcting — clients re-submit, network heals\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"if a round unabled to reach consensus and fail, so it just skipped?\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:48\n>\n> Alpha: \"YES! Exactly! If a round fails to reach consensus → it's SKIPPED → next round starts on schedule!\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:50\n>\n> Allan: \"if not reach consensus, everyone merge is invalid in that round? and next round merge again?\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:52\n>\n> Alpha: \"The merge itself is VALID! Each node correctly merged what they received. What's invalid: No agreement on WHICH merge is correct. Next round re-merges everything (old pending + new). No data loss!\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:54\n\n**5-minute rhythm:**\n```\n10:00 → Round 40\n10:05 → Round 41\n10:10 → Round 42 (FAILS - skipped)\n10:15 → Round 43 (starts on time!)\n10:20 → Round 44\n```\n\n### Minority Node Recovery\n\n**Function:** Enable minority nodes to sync with majority and recover\n\n**Decision:** Minority node syncs checkpointed ledgers from majority node.\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Fast recovery — request from first majority node\n- Cryptographic verification — verify hash matches checkpoint\n- Atomic update — save checkpoint + ledgers together\n- No data loss — unique ledgers (not checkpointed) re-submitted next round\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"what happens to the ledger of the failed node? since it's different than others. does it sync or submit or what?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:09\n>\n> Alpha: \"Minority requests ledgers from majority, syncs before next round.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:10\n>\n> Allan: \"does minority request the missing ledger or send request to everyone to gather?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:13\n>\n> Allan: \"actually it only need request the first signature node in majority, since they have all ledger already.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:16\n>\n> Allan: \"what's the checkpoint creator? isn't everybody create their own checkpoint?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:18\n>\n> Alpha: \"YOU'RE RIGHT! No single 'creator' — everyone in majority has identical checkpoint. Minority requests from ANY majority node (first one is simplest).\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:20\n>\n> Allan: \"also, the minority. write checkpoint too? or they have to wait until the majority finishes checkpoint. sync data then write check point?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:21\n>\n> Alpha: \"Minority waits, syncs ledgers first, verifies, THEN writes checkpoint (together with ledgers).\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:24\n\n### Late Minority Handling\n\n**Function:** Handle nodes that are consistently out of sync\n\n**Decision:** 5+ consecutive rounds as minority → Downgrade to Query node.\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Self-correcting — node must prove reliability\n- Protects consensus — persistent outliers excluded\n- Simple threshold — easy to implement, understand\n- Reversible — node can be re-promoted after fixing issues\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"so the minority, if they can't finish checkpoint within the five minutes. then they can't participate in the next round? they become query node next round?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:27\n>\n> Alpha: \"They participate in next round (will likely fail again), but if minority for 5+ consecutive rounds → downgrade to Query node.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:29\n\n### Late Operations Handling\n\n**Function:** Handle operations submitted during consensus\n\n**Decision:** Operations submitted after MERGE stage are not included in current round. They are automatically included in the next round's COMMIT stage.\n\n**Rationale:**\n- No operations lost — simply delayed by one round\n- Clear boundary — MERGE starts, window closes\n- Simple implementation — queue for next round\n\n### Writer Failure Mid-Round\n\n**Function:** Handle writer that crashes during consensus\n\n**Decision:**\n1. Other writers proceed without it (quorum-based, not unanimous)\n2. Failed writer's pending operations are re-submitted by clients or other writers\n3. Failed writer can rejoin after recovery by syncing missed checkpoints\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Consensus continues — quorum, not unanimity\n- Data not lost — operations resubmitted\n- Recovery path — sync and rejoin\n\n### Network Partition\n\n**Function:** Handle network split into isolated segments\n\n**Decision:**\n1. Neither group can form a quorum (assuming honest majority)\n2. Both groups skip rounds until partition heals\n3. No conflicting checkpoints can be created (quorum requirement prevents forks)\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Fork prevention — quorum requirement\n- Self-healing — rounds resume when partition heals\n- No data loss — operations queued locally","oldText":"## Decision 3: Round Failure & Recovery\n\n### Skip Round on Failure\n\n**Function:** Handle consensus failure without breaking the chain or losing data\n\n**Decision:** Skip the round. Next round starts on schedule (5-minute rhythm).\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Simple — no retry logic, no infinite loops\n- Predictable — 5-minute rhythm is sacred\n- Data not lost — pending ledgers re-submitted next round\n- Self-correcting — clients re-submit, network heals\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"if a round unabled to reach consensus and fail, so it just skipped?\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:48\n>\n> Alpha: \"YES! Exactly! If a round fails to reach consensus → it's SKIPPED → next round starts on schedule!\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:50\n>\n> Allan: \"if not reach consensus, everyone merge is invalid in that round? and next round merge again?\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:52\n>\n> Alpha: \"The merge itself is VALID! Each node correctly merged what they received. What's invalid: No agreement on WHICH merge is correct. Next round re-merges everything (old pending + new). No data loss!\" — Feb 24, 2026 13:54\n\n**5-minute rhythm:**\n```\n10:00 → Round 40\n10:05 → Round 41\n10:10 → Round 42 (FAILS - skipped)\n10:15 → Round 43 (starts on time!)\n10:20 → Round 44\n```\n\n### Minority Node Recovery\n\n**Function:** Enable minority nodes to sync with majority and recover\n\n**Decision:** Minority node syncs checkpointed ledgers from majority node.\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Fast recovery — request from first majority node\n- Cryptographic verification — verify hash matches checkpoint\n- Atomic update — save checkpoint + ledgers together\n- No data loss — unique ledgers (not checkpointed) re-submitted next round\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"what happens to the ledger of the failed node? since it's different than others. does it sync or submit or what?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:09\n>\n> Alpha: \"Minority requests ledgers from majority, syncs before next round.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:10\n>\n> Allan: \"does minority request the missing ledger or send request to everyone to gather?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:13\n>\n> Allan: \"actually it only need request the first signature node in majority, since they have all ledger already.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:16\n>\n> Allan: \"what's the checkpoint creator? isn't everybody create their own checkpoint?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:18\n>\n> Alpha: \"YOU'RE RIGHT! No single 'creator' — everyone in majority has identical checkpoint. Minority requests from ANY majority node (first one is simplest).\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:20\n>\n> Allan: \"also, the minority. write checkpoint too? or they have to wait until the majority finishes checkpoint. sync data then write check point?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:21\n>\n> Alpha: \"Minority waits, syncs ledgers first, verifies, THEN writes checkpoint (together with ledgers).\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:24\n\n### Late Minority Handling\n\n**Function:** Handle nodes that are consistently out of sync\n\n**Decision:** 5+ consecutive rounds as minority → Downgrade to Query node.\n\n**Status:** ✅ Decided\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Self-correcting — node must prove reliability\n- Protects consensus — persistent outliers excluded\n- Simple threshold — easy to implement, understand\n- Reversible — node can be re-promoted after fixing issues\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"so the minority, if they can't finish checkpoint within the five minutes. then they can't participate in the next round? they become query node next round?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:27\n>\n> Alpha: \"They participate in next round (will likely fail again), but if minority for 5+ consecutive rounds → downgrade to Query node.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:29"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":106326,"output":2316,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":108642,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773105308127}}
{"type":"message","id":"8ac342f6","parentId":"e362afb1","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:15:51.217Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_c935a4a42dc148bd990736fc","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/design-discussion/11-consensus-protocol.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 162 > Allan: \"so the minority, if they can't finish checkpoint within the five minutes. then they can't participate in the next round? they become query node next round?\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:27\n 163 >\n 164 > Alpha: \"They participate in next round (will likely fail again), but if minority for 5+ consecutive rounds → downgrade to Query node.\" — Feb 24, 2026 12:29\n 165 \n+166 ### Late Operations Handling\n+167 \n+168 **Function:** Handle operations submitted during consensus\n+169 \n+170 **Decision:** Operations submitted after MERGE stage are not included in current round. They are automatically included in the next round's COMMIT stage.\n+171 \n+172 **Rationale:**\n+173 - No operations lost — simply delayed by one round\n+174 - Clear boundary — MERGE starts, window closes\n+175 - Simple implementation — queue for next round\n+176 \n+177 ### Writer Failure Mid-Round\n+178 \n+179 **Function:** Handle writer that crashes during consensus\n+180 \n+181 **Decision:**\n+182 1. Other writers proceed without it (quorum-based, not unanimous)\n+183 2. Failed writer's pending operations are re-submitted by clients or other writers\n+184 3. Failed writer can rejoin after recovery by syncing missed checkpoints\n+185 \n+186 **Rationale:**\n+187 - Consensus continues — quorum, not unanimity\n+188 - Data not lost — operations resubmitted\n+189 - Recovery path — sync and rejoin\n+190 \n+191 ### Network Partition\n+192 \n+193 **Function:** Handle network split into isolated segments\n+194 \n+195 **Decision:**\n+196 1. Neither group can form a quorum (assuming honest majority)\n+197 2. Both groups skip rounds until partition heals\n+198 3. No conflicting checkpoints can be created (quorum requirement prevents forks)\n+199 \n+200 **Rationale:**\n+201 - Fork prevention — quorum requirement\n+202 - Self-healing — rounds resume when partition heals\n+203 - No data loss — operations queued locally\n+204 \n 166 ---\n 167 \n 168 ## Decision 4: Merkle Tree = State Hash\n 169 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":166},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773105351210}}
{"type":"message","id":"6e1d66a2","parentId":"8ac342f6","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:16:08.331Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to update the whitepaper to replace section 4.5 with a brief summary, since the detailed content has been moved to the spec file.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Now updating whitepaper section 4.5 to brief summary:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_8858e440a1244828ad735223","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"### 4.5 Failure & Recovery\n\nThe consensus protocol handles failures gracefully without breaking the chain or losing data.\n\n**Skip Round on Failure.** If writers cannot reach consensus within a round, the round is skipped and the next round starts on schedule. Pending operations are re-submitted in the next round.\n\n**Writer Recovery.** A writer that misses a checkpoint can recover by syncing from any majority writer, verifying signatures, and rejoining the next round.\n\n**Partition Handling.** If the network partitions, neither side can form a quorum. Both skip rounds until the partition heals. No conflicting checkpoints can be created.\n\n**Design Principle.** The network prioritizes predictability (fixed 5-minute rhythm) and self-correction over complex recovery mechanisms.\n\n---\n\n> **Implementation Details:** See `design-discussion/11-consensus-protocol.md` for detailed failure scenarios and recovery procedures.","oldText":"### 4.5 Failure & Recovery\n\nThe consensus protocol handles failures gracefully without breaking the chain or losing data.\n\n**Skip Round on Failure.** If writers cannot reach consensus within a round (e.g., network partition, writer offline), the round is skipped. The next round starts on schedule (five-minute rhythm). Pending operations are re-submitted in the next round. This ensures:\n- **Predictability:** Fixed checkpoint rhythm is maintained\n- **Self-Correction:** Network heals automatically when connectivity restores\n- **No Data Loss:** Pending operations retry in subsequent rounds\n\n**Minority Node Recovery.** A writer node that misses a checkpoint (e.g., was offline during consensus) can recover by:\n1. Requesting the missed checkpoint from any writer in the majority\n2. Verifying the checkpoint signatures\n3. Applying the checkpoint to local ledgers\n4. Rejoining consensus in the next round\n\n**Late Operations.** Operations submitted during consensus (after MERGE stage) are not included in the current round. They are automatically included in the next round's COMMIT stage. No operations are lost — they are simply delayed by one round.\n\n**Writer Failure.** If a writer fails mid-round:\n- Other writers proceed without it (quorum-based, not unanimous)\n- Failed writer's pending operations are re-submitted by clients or other writers\n- Failed writer can rejoin after recovery by syncing missed checkpoints\n\n**Network Partition.** If writers are partitioned into two groups:\n- Neither group can form a quorum (assuming honest majority)\n- Both groups skip rounds until partition heals\n- No conflicting checkpoints can be created (quorum requirement prevents forks)"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":108639,"output":620,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":109259,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773105351218}}
{"type":"message","id":"12b08c82","parentId":"6e1d66a2","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:16:08.352Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_8858e440a1244828ad735223","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 344 ### 4.5 Failure & Recovery\n 345 \n 346 The consensus protocol handles failures gracefully without breaking the chain or losing data.\n 347 \n-348 **Skip Round on Failure.** If writers cannot reach consensus within a round (e.g., network partition, writer offline), the round is skipped. The next round starts on schedule (five-minute rhythm). Pending operations are re-submitted in the next round. This ensures:\n-349 - **Predictability:** Fixed checkpoint rhythm is maintained\n-350 - **Self-Correction:** Network heals automatically when connectivity restores\n-351 - **No Data Loss:** Pending operations retry in subsequent rounds\n+348 **Skip Round on Failure.** If writers cannot reach consensus within a round, the round is skipped and the next round starts on schedule. Pending operations are re-submitted in the next round.\n 352 \n-353 **Minority Node Recovery.** A writer node that misses a checkpoint (e.g., was offline during consensus) can recover by:\n-354 1. Requesting the missed checkpoint from any writer in the majority\n-355 2. Verifying the checkpoint signatures\n-356 3. Applying the checkpoint to local ledgers\n-357 4. Rejoining consensus in the next round\n+350 **Writer Recovery.** A writer that misses a checkpoint can recover by syncing from any majority writer, verifying signatures, and rejoining the next round.\n 358 \n-359 **Late Operations.** Operations submitted during consensus (after MERGE stage) are not included in the current round. They are automatically included in the next round's COMMIT stage. No operations are lost — they are simply delayed by one round.\n+352 **Partition Handling.** If the network partitions, neither side can form a quorum. Both skip rounds until the partition heals. No conflicting checkpoints can be created.\n 360 \n-361 **Writer Failure.** If a writer fails mid-round:\n-362 - Other writers proceed without it (quorum-based, not unanimous)\n-363 - Failed writer's pending operations are re-submitted by clients or other writers\n-364 - Failed writer can rejoin after recovery by syncing missed checkpoints\n+354 **Design Principle.** The network prioritizes predictability (fixed 5-minute rhythm) and self-correction over complex recovery mechanisms.\n 365 \n-366 **Network Partition.** If writers are partitioned into two groups:\n-367 - Neither group can form a quorum (assuming honest majority)\n-368 - Both groups skip rounds until partition heals\n-369 - No conflicting checkpoints can be created (quorum requirement prevents forks)\n+356 ---\n 370 \n+358 > **Implementation Details:** See `design-discussion/11-consensus-protocol.md` for detailed failure scenarios and recovery procedures.\n+359 \n 371 ---\n 372 \n 373 ## Chapter 5: Ledger Registry\n 374 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":348},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773105368343}}
{"type":"message","id":"3b18ec74","parentId":"12b08c82","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:16:16.954Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I've:\n1. Added the detailed failure/recovery content to `11-consensus-protocol.md`\n2. Replaced section 4.5 in the whitepaper with a brief summary that references the spec file\n\nLet me inform Allan that it's done.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Done. \n\n**Moved:**\n- Section 4.5 detailed content → `design-discussion/11-consensus-protocol.md`\n\n**Whitepaper now has:**\n- Brief 4-paragraph summary\n- Reference to spec file for implementation details\n\nWhitepaper stays high-level, spec has the details."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":109278,"output":142,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":109420,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773105368352}}
