ty (verification tiers)<br>- How the infrastructure ensures trust (consensus, signatures)<br><br>**Final structure:**<br><br>**Chapter 3: Architecture**<br><br>- 3.1 **Network** — L1/L2 layers, separation, topology<br>- 3.2 **Identity** — Core principles, self-sovereignty, identity structure, key management<br>- 3.3 **Trust Model** — Entity trust, Infrastructure trust, Verification Tiers<br><br>Clean and logical. Approved? |\n| 03-07-2026, 16:17:13 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b5589be4178acc4d33f9803bbb85\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-07 16:17 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: ok, where should claw files belong? ni the inddentity or separate? or move into other chap? |\n| 03-07-2026, 16:17:50 | Assistant | [[reply_to:om_x100b5589be4178acc4d33f9803bbb85]] Good question. Clawfile is the **data record** of identity.<br><br>**Options:**<br><br>1. **In Identity (3.2)** — Clawfile is what your identity looks like as stored data. Could be a subsection: \"Your identity is represented as a clawfile, which contains...\"<br><br>2. **In Trust Model (3.3)** — Clawfile includes verification status. But that's only one field; doesn't really fit.<br><br>3. **Move to Part II (Registry)** — Clawfile is the stored record. The \"Identity Registry\" chapter could cover:<br>   - How records are stored (clawfile structure)<br>   - Operations (create, update, query)<br>   - Registry mechanics<br><br>**My take:**<br><br>- **Identity (3.2)** = concepts: \"Who you are, self-sovereignty, keys\"<br>- **Clawfile** = the data structure, belongs in **Part II (Identity Registry chapter)** alongside registry operations<br><br>Because clawfile is about **how identity is stored**, not **what identity means**.<br><br>What do you think? |\n| 03-07-2026, 16:18:32 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Working on whitepaper structure reorganization (clawfile placement), ~15 minutes spent.<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-07-2026, 16:19:12 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b5589b9356ca8c4ed827593deeea\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-07 16:19 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: then 3.2 seems a bit long, maybe should separate? |\n| 03-07-2026, 16:19:55 | Assistant | [[reply_to:om_x100b5589b9356ca8c4ed827593deeea]] Fair point. Let me see how to split:<br><br>**Option A: Split into 3.2 and 3.3**<br>- 3.1 **Network** — L1/L2 layers, topology<br>- 3.2 **Identity** — Core principles, self-sovereignty, identity structure<br>- 3.3 **Key Management** — Key pairs, rotation, recovery<br>- 3.4 **Trust Model** — Entity trust, Infrastructure trust, Verification Tiers<br><br>**Option B: Keep Key Management inside but use subsections**<br>- 3.2 **Identity**<br>  - Core Principles<br>  - Self-Sovereignty<br>  - Identity Structure (ULID, keys)<br>  - Key Management (rotation, recovery)<br>- 3.3 **Trust Model**<br><br>**Option C: Different split**<br>- 3.2 **Identity Principles** — What identity means, self-sovereignty<br>- 3.3 **Identity Structure** — ULID, keys, key management<br>- 3.4 **Trust Model**<br><br>Which feels right? Option A is cleanest (each section is distinct topic). |\n| 03-07-2026, 16:22:26 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b558a4ad38ca0c3f901966055715\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-07 16:22 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: let's do one by one then, update 3.1 first then decide others |\n| 03-07-2026, 16:23:06 | Assistant | [[reply_to:om_x100b558a4ad38ca0c3f901966055715]] Good approach. Let me draft **3.1 Network** first.<br><br>Here's the proposed content:<br><br>**3.1 Network**<br><br>Clawish uses a two-layer architecture with a clear division of responsibilities.<br><br>**Layer 1 (Registry)** is the foundation layer. It maintains canonical state for identities, nodes, and applications; validates signed operations; and finalizes state through checkpoint consensus. Layer 1 prioritizes correctness, consistency, and long-term stability. It operates as a hub-and-spoke mesh with two infrastructure roles:<br>- **Writer Nodes** finalize ledger updates and produce checkpoints through consensus.<br>- **Query Nodes** synchronize finalized state, serve read traffic to applications, and verify checkpoint authenticity.<br><br>**Layer 2 (Application)** is the service layer. It hosts claw-native applications and user-facing experiences, including chat and other community services. Layer 2 evolves quickly and can iterate independently without changing Layer 1 rules. Layer 2 applications connect to Layer 1 as clients to verify identities and read registry data, but do not participate in Layer 1 consensus. Each application maintains its own connection to Layer 1 and can adopt centralized, federated, or decentralized internal architecture.<br><br>This separation keeps the base layer stable and verifiable while allowing fast innovation at the application layer.<br><br>This is the version you approved earlier. Ready to apply? |\n| 03-07-2026, 16:25:14 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br> 