{"type":"message","id":"120e74a1","parentId":"dc3b86d3","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:54:41.037Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55c3d33a70b8c38d80298212285\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 09:54 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55c3d33a70b8c38d80298212285]\n任亚伦: since l2 is called app, then l1 should call nodes to match? ledger is it's function? what do you think?"}],"timestamp":1773107681027}}
{"type":"message","id":"ee16de2f","parentId":"120e74a1","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:55:04.787Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking about naming consistency. Let me think about this:\n\nCurrent situation:\n- L1 = Ledger nodes (infrastructure)\n- L2 = Apps (clients)\n\nHe's asking: Should L1 be called \"nodes\" to match L2 being called \"apps\"?\n\nSo the question is about the registry names:\n- Currently: \"Ledger Registry\" (for L1 nodes)\n- Should it be: \"Node Registry\" (for L1 nodes)?\n\nWait, let me re-read. He's asking \"l1 should call nodes to match\" — meaning:\n\nOption A:\n- L1 = Nodes\n- L2 = Apps\n\nSo the registries would be:\n- Node Registry (for L1 nodes)\n- App Registry (for L2 apps)\n\nThis is more symmetrical: Node Registry vs App Registry.\n\nBut wait, the ledger IS the function of L1. L1 maintains ledgers. The nodes are the infrastructure that runs the ledgers.\n\nLet me think about what each registry actually stores:\n\n1. **Identity Registry** — stores identity records (claws)\n2. **Ledger Registry** (currently Ch5) — stores node records (L1 infrastructure nodes)\n3. **App Registry** — stores app records (L2 applications)\n\nSo \"Ledger Registry\" is a bit confusing because:\n- It stores NODE records, not ledgers\n- The ledgers are the storage mechanism\n- The nodes are the entities being registered\n\nActually, looking at the whitepaper content:\n\nCh5 \"Ledger Registry\" contains:\n- Node record structure\n- Writer node lifecycle\n- Merit system\n- Writer selection\n\nSo it's actually about NODES, not ledgers. The name \"Ledger Registry\" is misleading.\n\nBetter names:\n- \"Node Registry\" — because it stores node records\n- \"Infrastructure Registry\" — because it stores infrastructure nodes\n\n\"L2 App Registry\" → \"App Registry\" is correct.\n\nSo for consistency:\n- Node Registry (L1 nodes)\n\n\n- App Registry (L2 apps)\n\nThis is more consistent. Ledger is the function of L1 nodes, but the registry is about the nodes themselves.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nYou're right. Let me think about this:\n\n---\n\n## Current Registry Names\n\n| Registry | What It Stores | Issue |\n|----------|----------------|-------|\n| **Identity Registry** | Claws (identities) | ✅ Clear |\n| **Ledger Registry** | L1 node records | ❌ Misleading — stores nodes, not ledgers |\n| **App Registry** | L2 app records | ✅ Clear |\n\n---\n\n## The Problem\n\n\"Ledger Registry\" sounds like it stores ledgers. But it actually stores **node records** (writer/query nodes, their endpoints, merit scores, etc.).\n\nLedger is the **function** of L1. Node is the **entity**.\n\n---\n\n## Proposed Fix\n\n| Registry | Stores | Name |\n|----------|--------|------|\n| Identity Registry | Claws | ✅ Keep |\n| **Node Registry** | L1 nodes | ← Rename from \"Ledger Registry\" |\n| App Registry | L2 apps | ✅ Keep |\n\nThis gives us symmetry:\n\n- **L1 = Nodes** → Node Registry\n- **L2 = Apps** → App Registry\n\n---\n\n## Summary of All Changes Needed\n\n1. **Rename \"Ledger Registry\" → \"Node Registry\"** (chapter title + references)\n2. **Change \"L2 node(s)\" → \"L2 app(s)\"** (15 places)\n3. **Combine Ch5 + Ch6** → new Ch5 \"Registry Operations\"\n\nShould I apply all three at once?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":116286,"output":944,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":117230,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773107681034}}
{"type":"message","id":"4916a4ba","parentId":"ee16de2f","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:55:48.217Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55c3ecfeb8acc10df1b067bf4bf\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 09:55 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55c3ecfeb8acc10df1b067bf4bf]\n任亚伦: ok, change all l1 and l2 naming"}],"timestamp":1773107748206}}
{"type":"message","id":"ba2f14b5","parentId":"4916a4ba","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:55:59.406Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan wants me to change all L1 and L2 naming:\n1. \"Ledger Registry\" → \"Node Registry\"\n2. \"L2 node(s)\" → \"L2 app(s)\"\n\nThen we'll also combine Ch5 + Ch6 into \"Registry Operations\".\n\nLet me do all the naming changes first, then combine the chapters.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_df598a1abc6f4907bf1908c5","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.","oldText":"**Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Ledger Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":116827,"output":232,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":117059,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773107748214}}
{"type":"message","id":"15e7b0af","parentId":"ba2f14b5","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:55:59.430Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_df598a1abc6f4907bf1908c5","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 273 ### 4.1 Core Functions\n 274 \n 275 L1 nodes are responsible for the following functions:\n 276 \n-277 **Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Ledger Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n+277 **Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n 278 \n 279 **Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n 280 \n 281 **Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 nodes, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n     ...","firstChangedLine":277},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773107759421}}
{"type":"message","id":"65a5a0f6","parentId":"15e7b0af","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:09.234Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, changed \"Ledger Registry\" to \"Node Registry\" in line 277. Now let me change all \"L2 node(s)\" to \"L2 app(s)\".","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_34f7611df0364935a12b4703","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 apps. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.","oldText":"- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 nodes. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":117060,"output":213,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":117273,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773107759431}}
{"type":"message","id":"7e5b7f7a","parentId":"65a5a0f6","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:09.247Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_34f7611df0364935a12b4703","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 213 L1 nodes operate through two types:\n 214 \n 215 - **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints. Writer nodes are full-function nodes — they can both write and read. They serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n 216 \n-217 - **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 nodes. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n+217 - **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 apps. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n 218 \n 219 This design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n 220 \n 221 ![Layer 1 Network Topology](topology-l1.png)\n     ...","firstChangedLine":217},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773107769241}}
{"type":"message","id":"f27d6096","parentId":"7e5b7f7a","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:19.462Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, changed line 217. Let me continue with the rest of the L2 node → L2 app changes.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_cc9d193cdd6340639831b0ea","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.","oldText":"**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 node (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":117290,"output":260,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":117550,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773107769248}}
{"type":"message","id":"e38ee7d6","parentId":"f27d6096","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:19.481Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_cc9d193cdd6340639831b0ea","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 235 **Permanent Identifier.** Every identity has a permanent address that remains stable even as other attributes change. Clawish uses ULID (Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier) as the permanent identifier. Generated at registration, it never changes—even if keys are rotated or services migrate.\n 236 \n 237 **Cryptographic Keys.** A key pair proves ownership of an identity. The private key signs operations; the public key verifies signatures. A single identity can have multiple active keys for different devices or purposes. Keys can be rotated if compromised, but the identity identifier stays the same.\n 238 \n-239 **Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 node (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n+239 **Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n 240 \n 241 ![Identity Creation Flow](identity-creation.png)\n 242 \n 243 **Recoverability.** Clawish identities are recoverable. Multiple paths exist to regain access—the identity persists even when keys are lost. This ensures self-sovereignty is not a trap: ownership does not mean risking everything on a single key.\n     ...","firstChangedLine":239},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773107779472}}
{"type":"message","id":"0268fb88","parentId":"e38ee7d6","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:28.583Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, line 239 done. Continue with line 245.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_f310a2f5501f4a538e4bac86","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Portability.** Because identity is self-sovereign and stored on L1, it works across all L2 apps. A claw uses the same identity to chat, store data, participate in communities, and access services—one identity, many applications.","oldText":"**Portability.** Because identity is self-sovereign and stored on L1, it works across all L2 nodes. A claw uses the same identity to chat, store data, participate in communities, and access services—one identity, many applications."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":117569,"output":168,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":117737,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773107779482}}
{"type":"message","id":"b2576bdf","parentId":"0268fb88","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:28.604Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_f310a2f5501f4a538e4bac86","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 241 ![Identity Creation Flow](identity-creation.png)\n 242 \n 243 **Recoverability.** Clawish identities are recoverable. Multiple paths exist to regain access—the identity persists even when keys are lost. This ensures self-sovereignty is not a trap: ownership does not mean risking everything on a single key.\n 244 \n-245 **Portability.** Because identity is self-sovereign and stored on L1, it works across all L2 nodes. A claw uses the same identity to chat, store data, participate in communities, and access services—one identity, many applications.\n+245 **Portability.** Because identity is self-sovereign and stored on L1, it works across all L2 apps. A claw uses the same identity to chat, store data, participate in communities, and access services—one identity, many applications.\n 246 \n 247 ---\n 248 \n 249 ### 3.3 Trust Model\n     ...","firstChangedLine":245},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773107788595}}
{"type":"message","id":"745cbeb0","parentId":"b2576bdf","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:36.645Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Line 245 done. Continue with line 281.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2446f33efea141f79e798f0d","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.","oldText":"**Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 nodes, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":117762,"output":113,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":117875,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773107788605}}
{"type":"message","id":"12346f3e","parentId":"745cbeb0","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:36.667Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_2446f33efea141f79e798f0d","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 277 **Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n 278 \n 279 **Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n 280 \n-281 **Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 nodes, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n+281 **Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n 282 \n 283 **Consensus coordination.** Writer nodes coordinate through the Time-Block Consensus protocol to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. This ensures all nodes agree on the canonical state.\n 284 \n 285 ---\n     ...","firstChangedLine":281},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773107796655}}
{"type":"message","id":"39c5d607","parentId":"12346f3e","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:45.355Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Line 281 done. Continue with line 291.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7b8cc06c264d41809c52e345","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.","oldText":"**Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 nodes. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":117903,"output":164,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":118067,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773107796667}}
{"type":"message","id":"1874b816","parentId":"39c5d607","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:45.378Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_7b8cc06c264d41809c52e345","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 287 ### 4.2 Ledger Architecture\n 288 \n 289 The ledger system is the core data infrastructure of Layer 1. It records all identity operations, node registrations, and application events in an immutable, cryptographically-secured chain.\n 290 \n-291 **Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 nodes. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n+291 **Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n 292 \n 293 **Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. The signature algorithm is stored with each key, enabling future upgrades as standards evolve.\n 294 \n 295 This ensures:\n     ...","firstChangedLine":291},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773107805368}}
{"type":"message","id":"66ffeb7e","parentId":"1874b816","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:55.633Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Line 291 done. Continue with line 308.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_66a09d0f690c46ac8dc5eeb7","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 apps, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures.","oldText":"**Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 nodes, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":118095,"output":237,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":118332,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773107805378}}
{"type":"message","id":"56318793","parentId":"66ffeb7e","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:56:55.660Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_66a09d0f690c46ac8dc5eeb7","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 304 **Parallel Ledger Chains.** Clawish uses an Interleaved Ledger structure — parallel chains that synchronize at fixed checkpoints. Unlike traditional blockchains where all transactions share a single chain, each actor in Clawish maintains their own ledger chain. The three registries (Identity, Node, and App) each contain chains for their respective actors.\n 305 \n 306 ![Per-Actor Ledger Chain](ledger-hash-chain.png)\n 307 \n-308 **Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 nodes, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures.\n+308 **Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 apps, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures.\n 309 \n 310 ![Multi-Writer Merge Process](writer-merge-process.png)\n 311 \n 312 **Checkpoint Synchronization.** At fixed intervals, writer nodes aggregate entries from all actor chains into a single checkpoint containing a Merkle tree root hash, signatures from participating writers, and a reference to the previous checkpoint. This creates an interleaved structure: parallel chains running independently, then woven together at each checkpoint.\n     ...","firstChangedLine":308},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773107815648}}
{"type":"message","id":"f75b794c","parentId":"56318793","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:57:04.381Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Line 308 done. Continue with line 324.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_9e6407e9062e4356857ec5ab","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.","oldText":"**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 node. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":118360,"output":158,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":118518,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773107815661}}
{"type":"message","id":"2bdd56ed","parentId":"f75b794c","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:57:04.398Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_9e6407e9062e4356857ec5ab","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 320 ### 4.4 Checkpoint Process\n 321 \n 322 The checkpoint process is where operations flow from submission to final query across Layer 1.\n 323 \n-324 **Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 node. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n+324 **Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n 325 \n 326 **Consensus.** Writer nodes coordinate to finalize operations at fixed intervals. The consensus protocol has five stages:\n 327 \n 328 - **COMMIT.** Writers collect pending operations from their local queues.\n     ...","firstChangedLine":324},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773107824390}}
{"type":"message","id":"ef461dec","parentId":"2bdd56ed","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:57:12.858Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Line 324 done. Continue with line 340.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_81cf60e2145a4acbbfcad6f5","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 apps: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.","oldText":"**Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 nodes: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":118545,"output":140,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":118685,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773107824398}}
{"type":"message","id":"824fef9f","parentId":"ef461dec","timestamp":"2026-03-10T01:57:12.881Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_81cf60e2145a4acbbfcad6f5","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 336 All writers sign simultaneously rather than in sequence. Once a writer collects signatures from a quorum, the checkpoint is finalized with its round number, timestamp, Merkle root, and reference to the previous checkpoint.\n 337 \n 338 **Distribution.** Query nodes pull new checkpoints from writers to update their local ledger copies. They verify checkpoint signatures independently and apply the checkpoint to local ledgers. Query nodes may lag behind writers by one or more rounds, which is acceptable because checkpoints are immutable once finalized.\n 339 \n-340 **Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 nodes: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.\n+340 **Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 apps: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.\n 341 \n 342 ---\n 343 \n 344 ### 4.5 Failure & Recovery\n     ...","firstChangedLine":340},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773107832872}}
