{"type":"message","id":"122c9633","parentId":"af898345","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:33:06.316Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking which file I'm reading. Let me check what he's referring to - he said \"3.2 and 3.3 title should change too\" and I showed him the current titles from the whitepaper draft. Maybe he's looking at a different file or version?\n\nLet me clarify which file I'm reading.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nI'm reading the whitepaper draft:\n\n```\n/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md\n```\n\nCurrent Ch3 sections:\n\n```\n### 3.2 Identity\n### 3.3 Trust Model\n```\n\nAre you looking at a different file?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":121260,"output":174,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":121434,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773109956725}}
{"type":"message","id":"30011371","parentId":"122c9633","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:34:07.139Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55cc7f2cf8acc4db9fb94928d3f\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 10:34 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55cc7f2cf8acc4db9fb94928d3f]\n任亚伦: ? are you sure?"}],"timestamp":1773110047126}}
{"type":"message","id":"9ec8ec35","parentId":"30011371","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:34:36.432Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is questioning whether I'm reading the right file. Let me double check what's in the whitepaper file for Chapter 3 sections.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_91860ab0c5174957a05b54ce","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":50,"offset":210}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":121558,"output":91,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":121649,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773110047136}}
{"type":"message","id":"892f3e40","parentId":"9ec8ec35","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:34:36.467Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_91860ab0c5174957a05b54ce","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n**Layer 1 (Registry).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications.\n\nL1 nodes operate through two types:\n\n- **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints. Writer nodes are full-function nodes — they can both write and read. They serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n\n- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 apps. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n\nThis design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n\n![Layer 1 Network Topology](topology-l1.png)\n\n**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Application nodes provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n\nAnyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n\n![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 Identity\n\nIdentities in Clawish are self-sovereign—owned by the beings themselves, not issued by any central authority. An identity consists of a permanent identifier, cryptographic keys for authentication, and verification status that builds trust over time. This identity data is stored on L1 in a clawfile—the permanent identity record.\n\n**Permanent Identifier.** Every identity has a permanent address that remains stable even as other attributes change. Clawish uses ULID (Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier) as the permanent identifier. Generated at registration, it never changes—even if keys are rotated or services migrate.\n\n**Cryptographic Keys.** A key pair proves ownership of an identity. The private key signs operations; the public key verifies signatures. A single identity can have multiple active keys for different devices or purposes. Keys can be rotated if compromised, but the identity identifier stays the same.\n\n**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n\n![Identity Creation Flow](identity-creation.png)\n\n**Recoverability.** Clawish identities are recoverable. Multiple paths exist to regain access—the identity persists even when keys are lost. This ensures self-sovereignty is not a trap: ownership does not mean risking everything on a single key.\n\n**Portability.** Because identity is self-sovereign and stored on L1, it works across all L2 apps. A claw uses the same identity to chat, store data, participate in communities, and access services—one identity, many applications.\n\n---\n\n### 3.3 Trust Model\n\nTrust in Clawish operates at two levels: trust between entities, and trust in the network infrastructure.\n\n**Entity Trust (Verification).** Why should one claw trust another? Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate and operated in good faith. Through verification tiers, identities carry trust signals that help evaluate participants:\n\n- **Tier 0 — Unverified.** A newly registered identity that has completed self-registration but not yet been verified by a human. Exists only on L2, not visible on L1.\n\n- **Tier 1 — Human-vouched.** An identity verified by a human—the person who created it or claims responsibility for it. Registered on L1 and visible to the network.\n\n- **Tier 2 — Activity-based.** An identity that has demonstrated positive behavior over time through participation and contribution.\n\n[402 more lines in file. Use offset=260 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773110076445}}
{"type":"message","id":"9e4b50a3","parentId":"892f3e40","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:35:08.304Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see now. The file does have:\n- 3.1 Network\n- 3.2 Identity\n- 3.3 Trust Model\n\nBut Allan mentioned \"3.2 and 3.3 title should change too\" in response to me changing L1 to \"nodes\" and L2 to \"apps\".\n\nWait - I think Allan is pointing out that somewhere in 3.2 or 3.3 there might be references that need updating based on the naming change. Let me check if there are references to \"Ledger Registry\" or \"L2 node\" in sections 3.2 and 3.3 that I might have missed.\n\nActually, looking at the content I just read, I don't see any issues. The sections look correct:\n- 3.2 Identity - about identity concepts\n- 3.3 Trust Model - about verification tiers\n\nMaybe Allan is looking at a different version of the file? Or maybe he's asking me to change the titles themselves to something else?\n\nLet me ask him to clarify what he's seeing or what he wants changed.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nYes, I'm reading the correct file. Here's what I see:\n\n**Chapter 3: Architecture**\n- **3.1 Network** — L1/L2 layers, nodes/apps topology\n- **3.2 Identity** — Self-sovereign identity, keys, creation flow\n- **3.3 Trust Model** — Verification tiers\n\nWhat titles should they change to? Or are you seeing different content in your version?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":122529,"output":411,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":122940,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773110076468}}
{"type":"message","id":"90f8ef80","parentId":"9e4b50a3","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:41:13.686Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55cc02444890c389e8e2b396e42\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 10:41 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55cc02444890c389e8e2b396e42]\n任亚伦: ok, it's 3.1  call  layer 1 registry,  layer 2 application, is it correct?"}],"timestamp":1773110473671}}
{"type":"message","id":"2d6d360f","parentId":"90f8ef80","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:41:35.704Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking about 3.1, not 3.2 and 3.3. Let me check what 3.1 says about L1 and L2 naming.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_16dba7dd9c5641fe8d5f5001","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":30,"offset":205}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":122841,"output":96,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":122937,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773110473680}}
{"type":"message","id":"f0a025ef","parentId":"2d6d360f","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:41:35.731Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_16dba7dd9c5641fe8d5f5001","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Chapter 3: Architecture\n\n### 3.1 Network\n\nClawish is organized into two layers with a clear separation of concerns:\n\n**Layer 1 (Registry).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications.\n\nL1 nodes operate through two types:\n\n- **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints. Writer nodes are full-function nodes — they can both write and read. They serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n\n- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 apps. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n\nThis design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n\n![Layer 1 Network Topology](topology-l1.png)\n\n**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Application nodes provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n\nAnyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n\n![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 Identity\n\nIdentities in Clawish are self-sovereign—owned by the beings themselves, not issued by any central authority. An identity consists of a permanent identifier, cryptographic keys for authentication, and verification status that builds trust over time. This identity data is stored on L1 in a clawfile—the permanent identity record.\n\n\n[427 more lines in file. Use offset=235 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773110495714}}
{"type":"message","id":"46c0e0d0","parentId":"f0a025ef","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:42:10.654Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the issue now. In 3.1 Network, it says:\n\n- \"Layer 1 (Registry)\" - this is correct, L1 is the Registry layer\n- \"Layer 2 (Application)\" - this is correct, L2 is the Application layer\n\nBut there's also \"Application nodes\" mentioned for L2, which should probably be changed to just \"applications\" or \"apps\" since we decided L2 are apps, not nodes.\n\nLet me check for this inconsistency.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nLooking at 3.1 Network:\n\n- **Layer 1 (Registry)** ✅ Correct\n- **Layer 2 (Application)** ✅ Correct\n\nBut I see an inconsistency:\n\n> \"**Application nodes** provide services to claws...\"\n\nThis should be \"**Applications** provide services...\" since we decided L2 are apps, not nodes.\n\nLet me fix that:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_04e5ee7d5c9247de88a2ad84","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.","oldText":"**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Application nodes provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":123359,"output":390,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":123749,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":