{"type":"message","id":"ed453b45","parentId":"3b79c87a","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:44:18.266Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking if \"Layer 1 (Registry)\" should be changed to \"Layer 1 (Nodes)\" to match the naming convention we established:\n\n- L1 = Nodes\n- L2 = Apps\n\nCurrently it says:\n- \"Layer 1 (Registry)\" - but Registry is the function, not the entity\n- \"Layer 2 (Application)\" - this is correct (Application = apps)\n\nTo be consistent with our decision (L1 nodes, L2 apps), it should be:\n- \"Layer 1 (Nodes)\" - because L1 consists of nodes\n- \"Layer 2 (Application)\" - because L2 consists of apps\n\nBut wait, there's also the concept of \"Registry\" as a function - L1 maintains the registries (Identity Registry, Node Registry, App Registry).\n\nLet me think about this more carefully:\n\nOption A: Keep \"Layer 1 (Registry)\" because L1's function is to maintain the registries\n- But this is inconsistent with L2 being called \"Application\" (the entity)\n\nOption B: Change to \"Layer 1 (Nodes)\" to match \"Layer 2 (Application)\"\n- L1 = Nodes (the entities)\n- L2 = Applications (the entities)\n- This is more consistent\n\nActually, I think Allan is right. If we're calling L2 \"Application\" (the entity type), then L1 should be \"Nodes\" (the entity type).\n\nSo:\n- Layer 1 (Nodes)\n- Layer 2 (Application)\n\nThis matches our naming convention:\n- L1 nodes, L2 apps","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nYou're right. To be consistent:\n\n| Layer | Entity | Should Be |\n|-------|--------|-----------|\n| L1 | Nodes | **Layer 1 (Nodes)** |\n| L2 | Apps | Layer 2 (Application) ✅ |\n\nCurrently:\n- \"Layer 1 (Registry)\" ← Registry is function, not entity\n- \"Layer 2 (Application)\" ← Application is entity ✅\n\nShould change to:\n- \"Layer 1 (Nodes)\"\n- \"Layer 2 (Application)\""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_1ce754dfb4c44f14b5d70ea2","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications.","oldText":"**Layer 1 (Registry).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":123894,"output":660,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":124554,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773110640052}}
{"type":"message","id":"d5f76f4c","parentId":"ed453b45","timestamp":"2026-03-10T02:44:18.285Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_1ce754dfb4c44f14b5d70ea2","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 207 ### 3.1 Network\n 208 \n 209 Clawish is organized into two layers with a clear separation of concerns:\n 210 \n-211 **Layer 1 (Registry).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications.\n+211 **Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications.\n 212 \n 213 L1 nodes operate through two types:\n 214 \n 215 - **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints. Writer nodes are full-function nodes — they can both write and read. They serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n     ...","firstChangedLine":211},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773110658274}}
