{"type":"message","id":"504397bf","parentId":"de653642","timestamp":"2026-03-10T03:56:51.793Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55cd26e1c4a8c3bd819e1e0a271\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 11:56 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55cd26e1c4a8c3bd819e1e0a271]\n任亚伦: ok, and 4.5 should be remove into spec doc"}],"timestamp":1773115011777}}
{"type":"message","id":"5565fbc4","parentId":"504397bf","timestamp":"2026-03-10T03:57:10.205Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan wants to:\n1. Move current 4.1 \"Core Functions\" to Ch5 as \"L1 Node Functions\"\n2. Rename Ch5 to \"L1 Nodes\"\n3. Rename Ch6 to \"L2 Applications\"\n4. Remove 4.5 \"Failure & Recovery\" to spec doc (we already did this earlier!)\n\nLet me apply these changes.\n\nFirst, let me check what 4.5 currently looks like - we already moved it to spec doc earlier today, so it should already have a brief summary and reference. Let me verify.\n\nActually, from earlier today, we already:\n1. Moved detailed 4.5 content to `design-discussion/11-consensus-protocol.md`\n2. Replaced 4.5 in whitepaper with brief summary\n\nSo I need to:\n1. Move current 4.1 to Ch5 as 5.1\n2. Renumber Ch4 sections (current 4.2→4.1, 4.3→4.2, 4.4→4.3, 4.5→4.4)\n3. Rename Ch5 title to \"L1 Nodes\"\n4. Renumber Ch5 sections (add new 5.1, old 5.1→5.2, etc.)\n5. Rename Ch6 title to \"L2 Applications\"\n\nLet me do this step by step.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nRight — we already moved 4.5 detailed content to spec doc earlier today. Let me apply all the changes:\n\n1. Move 4.1 \"Core Functions\" → Ch5 as \"L1 Node Functions\"\n2. Renumber Ch4 sections (4.2→4.1, 4.3→4.2, 4.4→4.3, 4.5→4.4)\n3. Rename Ch5 title to \"L1 Nodes\"\n4. Renumber Ch5 sections (new 5.1, old 5.1→5.2, etc.)\n5. Rename Ch6 title to \"L2 Applications\""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_53fa837a7fe54a9e9c3b2717","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":100,"offset":275}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":128591,"output":586,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":129177,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773115011789}}
{"type":"message","id":"138f405f","parentId":"5565fbc4","timestamp":"2026-03-10T03:57:10.223Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_53fa837a7fe54a9e9c3b2717","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"L1 nodes are responsible for the following functions:\n\n**Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n\n**Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n\n**Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n\n**Consensus coordination.** Writer nodes coordinate through the Time-Block Consensus protocol to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. This ensures all nodes agree on the canonical state.\n\n---\n\n### 4.2 Ledger Architecture\n\nThe ledger system is the core data infrastructure of Layer 1. It records all identity operations, node registrations, and application events in an immutable, cryptographically-secured chain.\n\n**Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n\n**Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. The signature algorithm is stored with each key, enabling future upgrades as standards evolve.\n\nThis ensures:\n- **Authenticity:** Only the key holder can create valid operations\n- **Integrity:** Any modification to the operation invalidates the signature\n- **Non-repudiation:** The actor cannot deny having created the operation\n\n---\n\n### 4.3 Interleaved Ledger\n\n**Parallel Ledger Chains.** Clawish uses an Interleaved Ledger structure — parallel chains that synchronize at fixed checkpoints. Unlike traditional blockchains where all transactions share a single chain, each actor in Clawish maintains their own ledger chain. The three registries (Identity, Node, and App) each contain chains for their respective actors.\n\n![Per-Actor Ledger Chain](ledger-hash-chain.png)\n\n**Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 apps, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures.\n\n![Multi-Writer Merge Process](writer-merge-process.png)\n\n**Checkpoint Synchronization.** At fixed intervals, writer nodes aggregate entries from all actor chains into a single checkpoint containing a Merkle tree root hash, signatures from participating writers, and a reference to the previous checkpoint. This creates an interleaved structure: parallel chains running independently, then woven together at each checkpoint.\n\n**Merkle Tree Integration.** Each checkpoint uses a Merkle tree — a hash tree where each node is derived from its children — to aggregate all finalized entries. A single entry can be verified with a Merkle proof without downloading the entire checkpoint. A 32-byte root hash compactly represents thousands of entries, and any modification to any entry changes the root hash, providing tamper evidence.\n\n![Layered Merkle Tree Checkpoint](merkle-tree-layered.png)\n\n---\n\n### 4.4 Checkpoint Process\n\nThe checkpoint process is where operations flow from submission to final query across Layer 1.\n\n**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n\n**Consensus.** Writer nodes coordinate to finalize operations at fixed intervals. The consensus protocol has five stages:\n\n- **COMMIT.** Writers collect pending operations from their local queues.\n- **SUBMIT.** Writers broadcast their pending operations to other writers.\n- **MERGE.** Each writer merges received operations into a unified ledger set.\n- **COMPARE.** Writers compare their merged ledger sets to ensure agreement.\n- **SEAL.** Writers sign the checkpoint and exchange signatures.\n\n![Checkpoint Consensus Protocol](consensus-checkpoint-overview.png)\n\nAll writers sign simultaneously rather than in sequence. Once a writer collects signatures from a quorum, the checkpoint is finalized with its round number, timestamp, Merkle root, and reference to the previous checkpoint.\n\n**Distribution.** Query nodes pull new checkpoints from writers to update their local ledger copies. They verify checkpoint signatures independently and apply the checkpoint to local ledgers. Query nodes may lag behind writers by one or more rounds, which is acceptable because checkpoints are immutable once finalized.\n\n**Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 apps: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.\n\n---\n\n### 4.5 Failure & Recovery\n\nThe consensus protocol handles failures gracefully without breaking the chain or losing data.\n\n**Skip Round on Failure.** If writers cannot reach consensus within a round, the round is skipped and the next round starts on schedule. Pending operations are re-submitted in the next round.\n\n**Writer Recovery.** A writer that misses a checkpoint can recover by syncing from any majority writer, verifying signatures, and rejoining the next round.\n\n**Partition Handling.** If the network partitions, neither side can form a quorum. Both skip rounds until the partition heals. No conflicting checkpoints can be created.\n\n**Design Principle.** The network prioritizes predictability (fixed 5-minute rhythm) and self-correction over complex recovery mechanisms.\n\n---\n\n> **Implementation Details:** See `design-discussion/11-consensus-protocol.md` for detailed failure scenarios and recovery procedures.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 5: Node Registry\n\n### 5.1 Node Registry Overview\n\nThe Node Registry maintains records for all infrastructure nodes:\n\n**Node Record Structure.** Each node record contains an identity_id (ULID) and public_key, node_type (Writer or Query), endpoint (network address), metrics (uptime percentage, response time, throughput, total rounds participated, successful rounds), merit_score (composite score for writer selection), status (Active, Inactive, or Suspended), and timestamps (created_at, updated_at).\n\n### 5.2 Writer Node Lifecycle\n\n1. **Registration.** Any claw can register as a node (initially as query node).\n2. **Probation.** New nodes operate in probation, building track record.\n3. **Promotion.** High-performing query nodes can be promoted to writer.\n\n[287 more lines in file. Use offset=375 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773115030210}}
{"type":"message","id":"b76ac615","parentId":"138f405f","timestamp":"2026-03-10T03:57:27.959Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to apply the restructure. Let me:\n\n1. First, get the current 4.1 content to move it to Ch5\n2. Then restructure Ch4 (remove 4.1, renumber)\n3. Then restructure Ch5 (add new 5.1, rename title, renumber sections)\n\nLet me do this step by step with edits.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_9fdd875d454c4bf19dca5689","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"## Chapter 4: Ledger System\n\n### 4.1 Ledger Architecture","oldText":"## Chapter 4: Ledger System\n\n### 4.1 Core Functions\n\nL1 nodes are responsible for the following functions:\n\n**Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n\n**Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n\n**Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n\n**Consensus coordination.** Writer nodes coordinate through the Time-Block Consensus protocol to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. This ensures all nodes agree on the canonical state.\n\n---\n\n### 4.2 Ledger Architecture"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":125254,"output":354,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":125608,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773115030223}}
{"type":"message","id":"c5a9dd2c","parentId":"b76ac615","timestamp":"2026-03-10T03:57:27.981Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_9fdd875d454c4bf19dca5689","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 269 ---\n 270 \n 271 ## Chapter 4: Ledger System\n 272 \n-273 ### 4.1 Core Functions\n+273 ### 4.1 Ledger Architecture\n 274 \n-275 L1 nodes are responsible for the following functions:\n-276 \n-277 **Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n-278 \n-279 **Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n-280 \n-281 **Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n-282 \n-283 **Consensus coordination.** Writer nodes coordinate through the Time-Block Consensus protocol to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. This ensures all nodes agree on the canonical state.\n-284 \n-285 ---\n-286 \n-287 ### 4.2 Ledger Architecture\n-288 \n 289 The ledger system is the core data infrastructure of Layer 1. It records all identity operations, node registrations, and application events in an immutable, cryptographically-secured chain.\n 290 \n 291 **Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n 292 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":273},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773115047968}}
