{"type":"message","id":"13070c66","parentId":"af0955ed","timestamp":"2026-03-10T03:58:37.901Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to restructure Ch5:1. Rename Ch5 title to \"L1 Nodes\"\n2. Add new 5.1 \"L1 Node Functions\" with the content from old 4.1\n3. Renumber old 5.1→5.2, 5.2→5.3, etc.Let me first update Ch5 title and add the new 5.1 section.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Now restructuring Ch5:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_127431b113654d1c86466715","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"## Chapter 5: L1 Nodes\n\n### 5.1 L1 Node Functions\n\nL1 nodes are responsible for the following functions:\n\n**Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n\n**Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n\n**Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n\n**Consensus coordination.** Writer nodes coordinate through the Time-Block Consensus protocol to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. This ensures all nodes agree on the canonical state.\n\n### 5.2 Node Registry Overview","oldText":"## Chapter 5: Node Registry\n\n### 5.1 Node Registry Overview"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":125942,"output":370,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":126312,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773115098631}}
