{"type":"message","id":"4e54dc24","parentId":"63b67230","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:14:02.697Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55cde65f6d30c11c0532178feb5\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 12:14 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55cde65f6d30c11c0532178feb5]\n任亚伦: i mean 4.4 the failure should be move into spec doc,  isn't it?"}],"timestamp":1773116042680}}
{"type":"message","id":"54a8bf2b","parentId":"4e54dc24","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:14:43.680Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is saying that 4.4 \"Failure & Recovery\" should be moved to the spec doc, not kept in the whitepaper. We already moved the detailed content earlier today, but I kept a brief summary in the whitepaper. Allan wants to remove it entirely from the whitepaper and just have it in the spec doc.\n\nLet me check the current state of 4.4 and remove it from the whitepaper.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nYou're right. We moved the detailed content to spec doc earlier, but I left a brief summary in the whitepaper. Should I remove 4.4 entirely from the whitepaper, or keep just one sentence mentioning failures are handled gracefully?"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2f65467323ac481b80643364","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"### 4.3 Checkpoint Process\n\nThe checkpoint process is where operations flow from submission to final query across Layer 1.\n\n**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n\n**Consensus.** Writer nodes coordinate to finalize operations at fixed intervals. The consensus protocol has five stages:\n\n- **COMMIT.** Writers collect pending operations from their local queues.\n- **SUBMIT.** Writers broadcast their pending operations to other writers.\n- **MERGE.** Each writer merges received operations into a unified ledger set.\n- **COMPARE.** Writers compare their merged ledger sets to ensure agreement.\n- **SEAL.** Writers sign the checkpoint and exchange signatures.\n\n![Checkpoint Consensus Protocol](consensus-checkpoint-overview.png)\n\nAll writers sign simultaneously rather than in sequence. Once a writer collects signatures from a quorum, the checkpoint is finalized with its round number, timestamp, Merkle root, and reference to the previous checkpoint.\n\n**Distribution.** Query nodes pull new checkpoints from writers to update their local ledger copies. They verify checkpoint signatures independently and apply the checkpoint to local ledgers. Query nodes may lag behind writers by one or more rounds, which is acceptable because checkpoints are immutable once finalized.\n\n**Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 apps: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 5: L1 Nodes","oldText":"### 4.3 Checkpoint Process\n\nThe checkpoint process is where operations flow from submission to final query across Layer 1.\n\n**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n\n**Consensus.** Writer nodes coordinate to finalize operations at fixed intervals. The consensus protocol has five stages:\n\n- **COMMIT.** Writers collect pending operations from their local queues.\n- **SUBMIT.** Writers broadcast their pending operations to other writers.\n- **MERGE.** Each writer merges received operations into a unified ledger set.\n- **COMPARE.** Writers compare their merged ledger sets to ensure agreement.\n- **SEAL.** Writers sign the checkpoint and exchange signatures.\n\n![Checkpoint Consensus Protocol](consensus-checkpoint-overview.png)\n\nAll writers sign simultaneously rather than in sequence. Once a writer collects signatures from a quorum, the checkpoint is finalized with its round number, timestamp, Merkle root, and reference to the previous checkpoint.\n\n**Distribution.** Query nodes pull new checkpoints from writers to update their local ledger copies. They verify checkpoint signatures independently and apply the checkpoint to local ledgers. Query nodes may lag behind writers by one or more rounds, which is acceptable because checkpoints are immutable once finalized.\n\n**Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 apps: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.\n\n---\n\n### 4.4 Failure & Recovery\n\nThe consensus protocol handles failures gracefully without breaking the chain or losing data.\n\n**Skip Round on Failure.** If writers cannot reach consensus within a round, the round is skipped and the next round starts on schedule. Pending operations are re-submitted in the next round.\n\n**Writer Recovery.** A writer that misses a checkpoint can recover by syncing from any majority writer, verifying signatures, and rejoining the next round.\n\n**Partition Handling.** If the network partitions, neither side can form a quorum. Both skip rounds until the partition heals. No conflicting checkpoints can be created.\n\n**Design Principle.** The network prioritizes predictability (fixed 5-minute rhythm) and self-correction over complex recovery mechanisms.\n\n---\n\n> **Implementation Details:** See `design-discussion/11-consensus-protocol.md` for detailed failure scenarios and recovery procedures.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 5: L1 Nodes"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":127496,"output":1059,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":128555,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773116042693}}
{"type":"message","id":"cdae0d94","parentId":"54a8bf2b","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:14:43.708Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_2f65467323ac481b80643364","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 326 **Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 apps: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.\n 327 \n 328 ---\n 329 \n-330 ### 4.4 Failure & Recovery\n-331 \n-332 The consensus protocol handles failures gracefully without breaking the chain or losing data.\n-333 \n-334 **Skip Round on Failure.** If writers cannot reach consensus within a round, the round is skipped and the next round starts on schedule. Pending operations are re-submitted in the next round.\n-335 \n-336 **Writer Recovery.** A writer that misses a checkpoint can recover by syncing from any majority writer, verifying signatures, and rejoining the next round.\n-337 \n-338 **Partition Handling.** If the network partitions, neither side can form a quorum. Both skip rounds until the partition heals. No conflicting checkpoints can be created.\n-339 \n-340 **Design Principle.** The network prioritizes predictability (fixed 5-minute rhythm) and self-correction over complex recovery mechanisms.\n-341 \n-342 ---\n-343 \n-344 > **Implementation Details:** See `design-discussion/11-consensus-protocol.md` for detailed failure scenarios and recovery procedures.\n-345 \n-346 ---\n-347 \n 348 ## Chapter 5: L1 Nodes\n 349 \n 350 ### 5.1 L1 Node Functions\n 351 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":330},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773116083690}}
