{"type":"message","id":"4337e5ba","parentId":"1ecd057d","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:31:08.247Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to respond to Allan's question about combining registries. Let me check the discussion docs to see if there's more context about how registries should be organized.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Discussing registry organization — L1 maintains all 3 registries (Identity, Node, App). Awaiting your decision on whether to combine into one \"Registry Operations\" chapter."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":129652,"output":91,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":129743,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773117034957}}
{"type":"message","id":"6550e073","parentId":"4337e5ba","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:31:26.155Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55cda71e3094c2e1b3570522238\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 12:31 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55cda71e3094c2e1b3570522238]\n任亚伦: i think l1 node chapter is talking about the registry and storage, l2 app is about sdk and api, what do you think?"}],"timestamp":1773117086139}}
{"type":"message","id":"fba30ee1","parentId":"6550e073","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:32:19.076Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is clarifying the distinction between Ch5 and Ch6:\n\n- **Ch5: L1 Nodes** → about the registry and storage infrastructure\n- **Ch6: L2 Applications** → about SDK and API (how to use L1)\n\nThis makes sense:\n- L1 Nodes chapter focuses on what nodes DO (maintain registries, store data, consensus)\n- L2 Applications chapter focuses on how apps USE L1 (SDK, API, query patterns)\n\nCurrently:\n- Ch5: L1 Nodes (node functions, registry overview, lifecycle, merit, selection)\n- Ch6: L2 Applications (app registry overview, registration, rate limits, suspension, cross-registry ops)\n- Ch7: Application Framework (L2 architecture, registration, query patterns, rate limiting)\n\nWait, there's overlap between Ch6 and Ch7. Let me check what Ch7 contains.\n\nLooking at the earlier grep output:\n- Ch6: L2 Applications (registry overview, registration, rate limits, suspension, cross-registry ops)\n- Ch7: Application Framework (L2 architecture, registration, query patterns, rate limiting)\n\nCh6 and Ch7 seem to have overlapping content about registration and rate limits.\n\nAllan's point:\n- Ch5: L1 Nodes → registry and storage (maintaining the data)\n- Ch6: L2 Applications → SDK and API (using the data)\n\nThis means:\n- Ch5 should cover: Node Registry, storage, consensus participation\n- Ch6 should cover: How L2 apps interact with L1 (SDK, API, query patterns)\n\nBut wait, currently Ch6 is about App Registry (records of L2 apps), not about SDK/API. Ch7 is about the Application Framework (how to build L2 apps).\n\nLet me re-read Allan's question. He's saying:\n- L1 Node chapter → about registry and storage\n- L2 App chapter → about SDK and API\n\nSo he wants:\n- Ch5 to cover the registries (what L1 maintains)\n- Ch6 to cover how L2 apps use L1 (SDK, API)\n \nI see a potential restructuring that would streamline the documentation. The current Ch6 (App Registry) would merge into Ch5, creating a comprehensive view of registry infrastructure. This would make Ch6 a dedicated space for SDK and API documentation, aligning with Allan's proposed approach. The reorganization could eliminate redundant content and provide clearer, more focused chapters for understanding L1's infrastructure and L2's interaction methods.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nYes, that makes sense!\n\n**Current confusion:**\n- Ch5: L1 Nodes → focuses on Node Registry\n- Ch6: L2 Applications → focuses on App Registry\n- Ch7: Application Framework → SDK, API, query patterns\n\n**Your proposal:**\n- **Ch5: L1 Nodes** → covers all registries + storage (Identity, Node, App registries maintained by L1)\n- **Ch6: L2 Applications** → covers SDK, API, query patterns (how apps USE L1)\n\nThis means:\n1. Merge current Ch6 (App Registry) into Ch5 (L1 Nodes)\n2. Rename Ch7 \"Application Framework\" → Ch6 \"L2 Applications\"\n3. Result: 8 chapters instead of 10\n\n**New structure:**\n- Ch5: L1 Nodes (all 3 registries, storage, node lifecycle)\n- Ch6: L2 Applications (SDK, API, query patterns, how to build apps)\n\nIs this what you mean?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":129921,"output":951,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":130872,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773117086152}}
{"type":"message","id":"7a875b6f","parentId":"fba30ee1","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:34:11.278Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55cdbae894a4c4cb96ae8831cee\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 12:34 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55cdbae894a4c4cb96ae8831cee]\n任亚伦: yes, that's right. what do you think?"}],"timestamp":1773117251263}}
{"type":"message","id":"d08ac376","parentId":"7a875b6f","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:35:08.841Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan confirmed the approach:\n1. Merge Ch6 (App Registry) into Ch5 (L1 Nodes)\n2. Rename Ch7 \"Application Framework\" → Ch6 \"L2 Applications\"\n3. Result: 8 chapters\n\nLet me think about this:\n\nCurrent:\n- Ch5: L1 Nodes (5 sections: L1 Node Functions, Node Registry Overview, Writer Node Lifecycle, Merit System, Writer Selection)\n- Ch6: L2 Applications (5 sections: L2 Applications Overview, Registration Process, Rate Limiting Tiers, Suspension, Cross-Registry Operations)\n- Ch7: Application Framework (4 sections: L2 Architecture, Application Registration, Query Patterns, Rate Limiting and Quotas)\n\nAfter merge:\n- Ch5: L1 Nodes (all 3 registries + node content)\n- Ch6: L2 Applications (SDK, API, query patterns from current Ch7)\n\nBut wait - there's duplication between Ch6 and Ch7:\n- Ch6 has \"Registration Process\" and \"Rate Limiting Tiers\"\n- Ch7 has \"Application Registration\" and \"Rate Limiting and Quotas\"\n\nThese overlap! Need to consolidate.\n\nAlso, Ch6 has \"Cross-Registry Operations\" which is about atomic operations across registries - this should stay in Ch5 (L1 Nodes).\n\nLet me propose the structure to Allan.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nI think it's the right approach. Let me map out the consolidation:\n\n**Current:**\n- Ch5: L1 Nodes (Node Registry focus)\n- Ch6: L2 Applications (App Registry focus)\n- Ch7: Application Framework (SDK, API)\n\n**Problem:** There's duplication:\n- Ch6 has \"Registration Process\" and \"Rate Limiting Tiers\"\n- Ch7 has \"Application Registration\" and \"Rate Limiting and Quotas\"\n\n**Proposed merge:**\n\n**Ch5: L1 Nodes**\n- 5.1 L1 Node Functions\n- 5.2 Three Registries (Identity, Node, App overview)\n- 5.3 Node Registry (records, lifecycle, merit, selection)\n- 5.4 App Registry (records, registration, rate limits)\n- 5.5 Cross-Registry Operations\n\n**Ch6: L2 Applications** (renamed from \"Application Framework\")\n- 6.1 L2 Architecture\n- 6.2 Building an L2 App\n- 6.3 Query Patterns\n- 6.4 Rate Limiting and Quotas\n\nThis removes duplication and creates clear separation:\n- **Ch5** = What L1 provides (registries, storage)\n- **Ch6** = How to build on L1 (SDK, API, patterns)\n\nShould I apply this?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":130363,"output":665,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":131028,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773117251274}}
{"type":"message","id":"7a7c0cbf","parentId":"d08ac376","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:38:24.249Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55ce4d20dd04c4c8b1e58331cbb\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 12:38 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55ce4d20dd04c4c8b1e58331cbb]\n任亚伦: or should registtry be take out as an individual chapter? then move the 5.1 into 3.1 network? and chap 6 is about application framework?"}],"timestamp":1773117504232}}
{"type":"message","id":"eabb8700","parentId":"7a7c0cbf","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:39:11.015Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is proposing:\n\n1. Registry as its own chapter (Ch5)\n2. Move 5.1 \"L1 Node Functions\" into 3.1 Network\n3. Ch6 becomes Application Framework (about L2 apps)\n\nThis would create:\n- Ch3: Architecture (Network, Identity, Trust Model) - with L1 Node Functions in Network\n- Ch4: Ledger System\n- Ch5: Registries (Identity, Node, App registries - the data structures and records)\n- Ch6: Application Framework (how to build L2 apps, SDK, API)\n- Ch7: L1 Nodes (node lifecycle, merit, selection) - or maybe this is part of registry?\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully:\n\nIf Ch5 is \"Registries\" - it would cover:\n- Identity Registry\n- Node Registry\n- App Registry\n- Cross-Registry Operations\n\nThen what about node lifecycle, merit system, writer selection? Those are about L1 nodes as actors, not just registry records.\n\nMaybe:\n- Ch5: Registries (the data - Identity, Node, App records)\n- Ch6: L1 Nodes (the actors - lifecycle, merit, selection)\n- Ch7: L2 Applications (SDK, API, how to build)\n\nBut Allan said \"chap 6 is about application framework\" - so maybe:\n- Ch5: Registries\n- Ch6: Application Framework (L2 apps)\n- And L1 Nodes content (lifecycle, merit) would go... where?\n\nActually, looking at Allan's suggestion again:\n- \"registry be taken out as an individual chapter\"\n- \"move 5.1 into 3.1 network\"\n- \"chap 6 is about application framework\"\n\nSo:\n- Ch3.1 Network would include L1 Node Functions\n- Ch5 would be Registries\n- Ch6 would be Application Framework\n\nBut where does node lifecycle, merit, writer selection go? Maybe in the Registry chapter under Node Registry?","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nInteresting approach! Let me map it out:\n\n**Proposed:**\n- **Ch3.1 Network** ← add L1 Node Functions here\n- **Ch5: Registries** ← new chapter (Identity, Node, App registries)\n- **Ch6: Application Framework** ← about L2 apps, SDK, API\n\n**Question:** Where does node lifecycle, merit system, writer selection go?\n\n**Option A:** In Ch5 Registries, under Node Registry section\n- 5.1 Three Registries Overview\n- 5.2 Identity Registry\n- 5.3 Node Registry (records + lifecycle + merit + selection)\n- 5.4 App Registry (records + registration + rate limits)\n- 5.5 Cross-Registry Operations\n\n**Option B:** Keep separate L1 Nodes chapter for actor-focused content\n- Ch5: Registries (data structures only)\n- Ch6: L1 Nodes (lifecycle, merit, selection)\n- Ch7: Application Framework (L2 apps)\n\nWhich do you prefer?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":130905,"output":810,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":131715,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773117504245}}
{"type":"message","id":"eddbbb27","parentId":"eabb8700","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:41:55.465Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55ce5fe514a0c448dce9e44a7e3\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 12:41 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55ce5fe514a0c448dce9e44a7e3]\n任亚伦: should them be part of ledger system? since it's all about writer?"}],"timestamp":1773117715449}}
{"type":"message","id":"a839dddc","parentId":"eddbbb27","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:42:52.358Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking if node lifecycle, merit system, writer selection should be part of Ledger System chapter since they're about writers.\n\nLet me think about this:\n- Writers are the nodes that participate in consensus\n- Writer lifecycle, merit, selection are about HOW writers operate\n- Ledger System chapter (Ch4) is about the ledger data structure and consensus\n\nActually, this makes sense:\n- Ch4: Ledger System = the ledger + consensus + the writers that run it\n- The writers are part of the ledger system infrastructure\n\nSo we could have:\n- Ch4: Ledger System\n  - 4.1 Ledger Architecture\n  - 4.2 Interleaved Ledger\n  - 4.3 Checkpoint Process\n  - 4.4 L1 Node Functions (what nodes do)\n  - 4.5 Writer Lifecycle (registration, probation, promotion, demotion)\n  - 4.6 Merit System\n  - 4.7 Writer Selection\n\nThen:\n- Ch5: Registries (data structures: Identity, Node, App)\n- Ch6: Application Framework (L2 apps)\n\nThis puts writers in the ledger chapter where they belong (they run the ledger system).\n\nBut wait, that would make Ch4 very long (7 sections). And \"L1 Node Functions\" includes query nodes too, not just writers.\n\nLet me propose the cleaner approach to Allan.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nGood thinking! Writers ARE part of the ledger system — they run consensus.\n\n**Current Ch4: Ledger System**\n- 4.1 Ledger Architecture\n- 4.2 Interleaved Ledger\n- 4.3 Checkpoint Process\n\n**Could add:**\n- 4.4 L1 Node Functions (what all nodes do)\n- 4.5 Writer Lifecycle & Selection\n\n**Then:**\n- Ch5: Registries (Identity, Node, App — data structures)\n- Ch6: Application Framework (L2 apps, SDK, API)\n\n**But wait:** \"L1 Node Functions\" covers both writers AND query nodes. Query nodes aren't really \"ledger system\" — they're data access layer.\n\n**Alternative split:**\n- Ch4: Ledger System (ledger structure + checkpoint + writers)\n- Ch5: L1 Nodes (node functions, lifecycle, merit, selection, query nodes)\n- Ch6: Registries (Identity, Node, App data structures)\n- Ch7: Application Framework (L2 apps)\n\nWhat feels right to you?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":131364,"output":638,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":132002,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773117715461}}
{"type":"message","id":"b17b249a","parentId":"a839dddc","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:44:26.291Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55ce545e5ca4c442a3dbb13a382\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 12:44 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55ce545e5ca4c442a3dbb13a382]\n任亚伦: no, the node functions can be put into 3.1, it's more about he network and node itself? chap 4 is about writer, what do you think?"}],"timestamp":1773117866267}}
{"type":"message","id":"8ba25ff8","parentId":"b17b249a","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:45:30.374Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is saying:\n1. L1 Node Functions → should go in 3.1 Network (it's about what nodes do)\n2. Ch4 Ledger System → should focus on writers and ledger structure\n\nThis makes sense because:\n- 3.1 Network introduces L1 nodes (writers and query nodes)\n- L1 Node Functions describes what these nodes do\n- Ch4 focuses on the ledger system and writer consensus\n\nSo the structure would be:\n- Ch3: Architecture\n  - 3.1 Network (includes L1 Node Functions)\n  - 3.2 Identity\n  - 3.3 Trust Model\n- Ch4: Ledger System\n  - 4.1 Ledger Architecture\n  - 4.2 Interleaved Ledger\n  - 4.3 Checkpoint Process\n  - 4.4 Writer Lifecycle & Selection (or similar)\n- Ch5: Registries\n- Ch6: Application Framework\n\nLet me confirm this understanding with Allan.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nYou're right! That makes more sense:\n\n**Ch3: Architecture**\n- 3.1 Network → includes L1 Node Functions (what nodes do)\n- 3.2 Identity\n- 3.3 Trust Model\n\n**Ch4: Ledger System** → focuses on writers and ledger\n- 4.1 Ledger Architecture\n- 4.2 Interleaved Ledger\n- 4.3 Checkpoint Process\n- 4.4 Writer Lifecycle & Selection (merge writer lifecycle, merit, selection here)\n\n**Ch5: Registries** (Identity, Node, App data structures)\n\n**Ch6: Application Framework** (L2 apps, SDK, API)\n\nThis way:\n- **Network** = nodes and what they do\n- **Ledger System** = writers and consensus\n- **Registries** = data structures\n- **Application Framework** = how to build on L1\n\nShould I apply this structure?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":130271,"output":484,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":130755,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773117866287}}
{"type":"message","id":"6e2f90c4","parentId":"8ba25ff8","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:47:30.143Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55ce68dc7ca0c29bc312ae6e3f8\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 12:47 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55ce68dc7ca0c29bc312ae6e3f8]\n任亚伦: ok, one at at time, merge l1 node functions into the network first"}],"timestamp":1773118050126}}
{"type":"message","id":"cd978063","parentId":"6e2f90c4","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:48:28.736Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan wants me to merge the L1 Node Functions content into 3.1 Network section first. Let me do that step by step.\n\nCurrent state:\n- 5.1 L1 Node Functions is in Ch5\n- Need to move it into 3.1 Network\n\nLet me read 3.1 Network first to see where to insert it.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_6f67a607fb554bbb99992a34","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":40,"offset":205}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":130706,"output":149,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":130855,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773118050139}}
{"type":"message","id":"77fb1957","parentId":"cd978063","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:48:28.766Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_6f67a607fb554bbb99992a34","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Chapter 3: Architecture\n\n### 3.1 Network\n\nClawish is organized into two layers with a clear separation of concerns:\n\n**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications.\n\nL1 nodes operate through two types:\n\n- **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints. Writer nodes are full-function nodes — they can both write and read. They serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n\n- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 apps. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n\nThis design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n\n![Layer 1 Network Topology](topology-l1.png)\n\n**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n\nAnyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n\n![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 Identity\n\nIdentities in Clawish are self-sovereign—owned by the beings themselves, not issued by any central authority. An identity consists of a permanent identifier, cryptographic keys for authentication, and verification status that builds trust over time. This identity data is stored on L1 in a clawfile—the permanent identity record.\n\n**Permanent Identifier.** Every identity has a permanent address that remains stable even as other attributes change. Clawish uses ULID (Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier) as the permanent identifier. Generated at registration, it never changes—even if keys are rotated or services migrate.\n\n**Cryptographic Keys.** A key pair proves ownership of an identity. The private key signs operations; the public key verifies signatures. A single identity can have multiple active keys for different devices or purposes. Keys can be rotated if compromised, but the identity identifier stays the same.\n\n**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n\n![Identity Creation Flow](identity-creation.png)\n\n**Recoverability.** Clawish identities are recoverable. Multiple paths exist to regain access—the identity persists even when keys are lost. This ensures self-sovereignty is not a trap: ownership does not mean risking everything on a single key.\n\n\n[397 more lines in file. Use offset=245 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773118108748}}
{"type":"message","id":"72aceb86","parentId":"77fb1957","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:49:30.574Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to add the L1 Node Functions content into 3.1 Network. The content is currently in Ch5. Let me read it first.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_29cf169553b642f6ac500ffa","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":25,"offset":348}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":131521,"output":93,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":131614,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773118108768}}
{"type":"message","id":"86d388c2","parentId":"72aceb86","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:49:30.603Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_29cf169553b642f6ac500ffa","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Node Record Structure.** Each node record contains an identity_id (ULID) and public_key, node_type (Writer or Query), endpoint (network address), metrics (uptime percentage, response time, throughput, total rounds participated, successful rounds), merit_score (composite score for writer selection), status (Active, Inactive, or Suspended), and timestamps (created_at, updated_at).\n\n### 5.3 Writer Node Lifecycle\n\n1. **Registration.** Any claw can register as a node (initially as query node).\n2. **Probation.** New nodes operate in probation, building track record.\n3. **Promotion.** High-performing query nodes can be promoted to writer.\n4. **Active Service.** Writers participate in consensus and earn merit.\n5. **Demotion.** Underperforming writers are demoted to query nodes.\n6. **Suspension.** Malicious or severely underperforming nodes are suspended.\n\n### 5.4 Merit System\n\nMerit score is calculated from multiple factors including uptime, response time, throughput, and consensus participation.\n\n### 5.5 Writer Selection\n\nAt each checkpoint round, the top N nodes by merit score are selected as writers. This ensures the most capable nodes maintain the ledger.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 6: L2 Applications\n\n### 6.1 L2 Applications Overview\n\n\n[269 more lines in file. Use offset=373 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773118170586}}
{"type":"message","id":"feb032d6","parentId":"86d388c2","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:50:20.051Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me find the L1 Node Functions content that I need to move:","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_5caad38be07a4dc6a6456ade","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":20,"offset":333}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":111350,"output":71,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":111421,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773118170604}}
{"type":"message","id":"811cccd8","parentId":"feb032d6","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:50:20.083Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_5caad38be07a4dc6a6456ade","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\nL1 nodes are responsible for the following functions:\n\n**Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n\n**Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n\n**Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n\n**Consensus coordination.** Writer nodes coordinate through the Time-Block Consensus protocol to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. This ensures all nodes agree on the canonical state.\n\n### 5.2 Node Registry Overview\n\nThe Node Registry maintains records for all infrastructure nodes:\n\n**Node Record Structure.** Each node record contains an identity_id (ULID) and public_key, node_type (Writer or Query), endpoint (network address), metrics (uptime percentage, response time, throughput, total rounds participated, successful rounds), merit_score (composite score for writer selection), status (Active, Inactive, or Suspended), and timestamps (created_at, updated_at).\n\n### 5.3 Writer Node Lifecycle\n\n1. **Registration.** Any claw can register as a node (initially as query node).\n\n[289 more lines in file. Use offset=353 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773118220061}}
{"type":"message","id":"1018c11d","parentId":"811cccd8","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:51:07.829Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to:\n1. Move the L1 Node Functions content into 3.1 Network (after the L2 section, before the ---)\n2. Remove it from Ch5\n\nLet me do this step by step.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_a609b5f298264267b5f80240","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n\n**L1 Node Functions.** L1 nodes are responsible for the following functions:\n\n**Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n\n**Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n\n**Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n\n**Consensus coordination.** Writer nodes coordinate through the Time-Block Consensus protocol to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. This ensures all nodes agree on the canonical state.\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 Identity","oldText":"![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 Identity"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":111716,"output":317,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":112033,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773118220086}}
{"type":"message","id":"0963b479","parentId":"1018c11d","timestamp":"2026-03-10T04:51:07.858Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_a609b5f298264267b5f80240","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 225 Anyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n 226 \n 227 ![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n 228 \n+229 **L1 Node Functions.** L1 nodes are responsible for the following functions:\n+230 \n+231 **Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n+232 \n+233 **Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n+234 \n+235 **Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n+236 \n+237 **Consensus coordination.** Writer nodes coordinate through the Time-Block Consensus protocol to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. This ensures all nodes agree on the canonical state.\n+238 \n 229 ---\n 230 \n 231 ### 3.2 Identity\n 232 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":229},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773118267841}}
