{"type":"message","id":"07bcda35","parentId":"26457ce0","timestamp":"2026-03-10T05:35:59.298Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55ce95188080c3dc14b8ec8f9c8\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 13:35 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55ce95188080c3dc14b8ec8f9c8]\n任亚伦: show.me whole 3.1"}],"timestamp":1773120959285}}
{"type":"message","id":"600c8e08","parentId":"07bcda35","timestamp":"2026-03-10T05:36:20.312Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan wants to see the whole proposed 3.1 Network section with the one-sentence functions description integrated. Let me write it out.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\n**Proposed 3.1 Network:**\n\n---\n\n### 3.1 Network\n\nClawish is organized into two layers with a clear separation of concerns:\n\n**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications. L1 nodes store all registry data (Identity, Node, and App registries) in ledgers and derived state tables, verify signed operations, record them to the appropriate ledgers, and serve query requests from L2 applications.\n\nL1 nodes operate through two types:\n\n- **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. Writer nodes serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n\n- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 applications. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n\nThis design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n\n![Layer 1 Network Topology](topology-l1.png)\n\n**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n\nAnyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n\n![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n\n---\n\n**Changes from current:**\n1. Removed separate \"**L1 Node Functions.**\" heading\n2. Functions integrated into one sentence after Layer 1 description\n3. Removed redundancy (consensus mentioned only in Writer Nodes)\n\nApprove?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":119271,"output":491,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":119762,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773120959295}}
{"type":"message","id":"b9822fd5","parentId":"600c8e08","timestamp":"2026-03-10T05:43:28.114Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55ceb93f54a4c31bde63e2a14a1\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 13:43 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55ceb93f54a4c31bde63e2a14a1]\n任亚伦: ok, update"}],"timestamp":1773121408092}}
{"type":"message","id":"e6dc8c95","parentId":"b9822fd5","timestamp":"2026-03-10T05:44:39.700Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan approved the 3.1 Network rewrite. I need to update the whitepaper with the proposed text.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_28f0763354e64f4f8110ec2b","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"## Chapter 3: Architecture\n\n### 3.1 Network\n\nClawish is organized into two layers with a clear separation of concerns:\n\n**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications. L1 nodes store all registry data (Identity, Node, and App registries) in ledgers and derived state tables, verify signed operations, record them to the appropriate ledgers, and serve query requests from L2 applications.\n\nL1 nodes operate through two types:\n\n- **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. Writer nodes serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n\n- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 applications. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n\nThis design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n\n![Layer 1 Network Topology](topology-l1.png)\n\n**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n\nAnyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n\n![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 Identity","oldText":"## Chapter 3: Architecture\n\n### 3.1 Network\n\nClawish is organized into two layers with a clear separation of concerns:\n\n**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications.\n\n**L1 Node Functions.** L1 nodes are responsible for the following functions:\n\n**Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n\n**Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n\n**Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n\n**Consensus coordination.** Writer nodes coordinate through the Time-Block Consensus protocol to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. This ensures all nodes agree on the canonical state.\n\nL1 nodes operate through two types:\n\n- **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints. Writer nodes are full-function nodes — they can both write and read. They serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n\n- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 apps. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n\nThis design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n\n![Layer 1 Network Topology](topology-l1.png)\n\n**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n\nAnyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n\n![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 Identity"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":119937,"output":984,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":120921,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773121408109}}
{"type":"message","id":"0c1a1530","parentId":"e6dc8c95","timestamp":"2026-03-10T05:44:39.730Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_28f0763354e64f4f8110ec2b","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 207 ### 3.1 Network\n 208 \n 209 Clawish is organized into two layers with a clear separation of concerns:\n 210 \n-211 **Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications.\n+211 **Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications. L1 nodes store all registry data (Identity, Node, and App registries) in ledgers and derived state tables, verify signed operations, record them to the appropriate ledgers, and serve query requests from L2 applications.\n 212 \n-213 **L1 Node Functions.** L1 nodes are responsible for the following functions:\n-214 \n-215 **Data storage.** L1 nodes store all registry data — the Identity Registry, Node Registry, and App Registry. Data is stored in ledgers (append-only logs) and derived state tables for fast queries.\n-216 \n-217 **Ledger management.** When an operation is submitted, L1 nodes verify the signature against the registered public key, then record the operation in the appropriate ledger. This ensures only legitimate operations are accepted.\n-218 \n-219 **Query service.** L1 nodes provide query service to L2 apps, enabling apps to verify identities and read registry data.\n-220 \n-221 **Consensus coordination.** Writer nodes coordinate through the Time-Block Consensus protocol to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. This ensures all nodes agree on the canonical state.\n-222 \n 223 L1 nodes operate through two types:\n 224 \n-225 - **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints. Writer nodes are full-function nodes — they can both write and read. They serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n+215 - **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. Writer nodes serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n 226 \n-227 - **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 apps. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n+217 - **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 applications. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n 228 \n 229 This design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n 230 \n 231 ![Layer 1 Network Topology](topology-l1.png)\n     ...","firstChangedLine":211},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773121479711}}
