{"type":"message","id":"b5388a0c","parentId":"95d67f19","timestamp":"2026-03-10T07:42:45.638Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking about cross-registry operations - whether it should be combined into 3.3 Registry section.\n\nCurrently I put a brief mention in 3.3:\n\"Some operations span multiple registries — a claw registering an app, a node being promoted to writer. These cross-registry operations are coordinated within a single checkpoint round for atomicity.\"\n\nThe old Ch6.5 had more detail about cross-registry operations. I should ask Allan if he wants:\n1. Just the brief mention in 3.3 (current)\n2. More detail in 3.3\n3. Or keep it somewhere else\n\nLet me show him what's currently in 3.3 and ask.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nI put a brief mention in 3.3:\n\n> Some operations span multiple registries — a claw registering an app, a node being promoted to writer. These cross-registry operations are coordinated within a single checkpoint round for atomicity.\n\n**Old Ch6.5 had more detail:**\n- Atomic Operations explanation\n- Coordination explanation\n- Example: App Registration\n- Integrity explanation\n\n**Question:** Is the brief mention enough for the whitepaper? Or should I add more?\n\nThe detailed cross-registry examples (like \"developer submits app registration request, system verifies identity...\") feel like implementation detail — maybe better in spec docs.\n\nWhat do you think?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":136596,"output":344,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":136940,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773128504942}}
{"type":"message","id":"cce3cecd","parentId":"b5388a0c","timestamp":"2026-03-10T07:42:46.612Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I put a brief mention in 3.3:\n\n> Some operations span multiple registries — a claw registering an app, a node being promoted to writer. These cross-registry operations are coordinated within a single checkpoint round for atomicity.\n\n**Old Ch6.5 had more detail:**\n- Atomic Operations explanation\n- Coordination explanation\n- Example: App Registration\n- Integrity explanation\n\n**Question:** Is the brief mention enough for the whitepaper? Or should I add more?\n\nThe detailed cross-registry examples (like \"developer submits app registration request, system verifies identity...\") feel like implementation detail — maybe better in spec docs.\n\nWhat do you think?"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773128566612}}
{"type":"message","id":"b590b2d1","parentId":"cce3cecd","timestamp":"2026-03-10T08:27:15.932Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55c910e938b8c44b85ed99f0443\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 16:27 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55c910e938b8c44b85ed99f0443]\n任亚伦: I think a detail can be put in the spec. Here just need describe."}],"timestamp":1773131235908}}
{"type":"message","id":"440e905f","parentId":"b590b2d1","timestamp":"2026-03-10T08:27:32.440Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan confirms that the detail should go in spec, and here we just need to describe conceptually. The brief mention I put in 3.3 is good enough.\n\nLet me check if the cross-registry operations content was preserved somewhere or if I need to add it to a spec file.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Good. The brief mention in 3.3 is sufficient.\n\nLet me save the detailed cross-registry content to the spec file:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7224733d6f9848c5a3e5ce31","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/design-discussion/12-ledger-structure.md","limit":50,"offset":250}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":135674,"output":165,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":135839,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773131235921}}
{"type":"message","id":"73eae014","parentId":"440e905f","timestamp":"2026-03-10T08:27:32.464Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_7224733d6f9848c5a3e5ce31","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\nIf attacker modifies ANY ledger:\n- Merkle root changes\n- state_hash changes\n- Signatures no longer match\n- Checkpoint is INVALID\n\nTo fake data, attacker must:\n1. Modify the ledger\n2. Recompute Merkle root\n3. Forge 2+ writer signatures\n4. Control majority of writers\n\n### Single-Ledger Verification\n\n**Problem:** How do we verify a single ledger without downloading all data?\n\n**Solution:** Merkle proof (sibling hashes along path to root).\n\nQuery node:\n1. Get ledger + Merkle proof from node\n2. Reconstruct root from ledger + proof\n3. Compare with checkpoint.state_hash\n4. Match? Ledger is authentic!\n\nNo need to download all ledgers!\n\n---\n\n## Tradeoffs\n\n| Aspect | Decision | Why |\n|--------|----------|-----|\n| **Table structure** | Single unified table | Simpler schema, easier queries |\n| **Pending distinction** | checkpoint_round tag (NULL vs NOT NULL) | Clear, efficient, atomic |\n| **State hash** | Merkle root | Enables efficient proofs |\n| **Ledger ordering** | ULID sort | Deterministic, timestamp embedded |\n\n---\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Separate Tables per Dimension (Rejected)\n\n```\nactor_ledgers, node_ledgers, app_ledgers\n```\n\n**Rejected because:**\n- 3x complexity (3 tables, 3x queries)\n\n[42 more lines in file. Use offset=300 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773131252451}}
{"type":"message","id":"d08836f9","parentId":"73eae014","timestamp":"2026-03-10T08:27:55.076Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I should add the cross-registry operations detail to the spec file. Let me append it.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_07caf7ee95304d4ca4b66fe6","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/design-discussion/12-ledger-structure.md","newText":"## Cross-Registry Operations\n\nSome operations span multiple registries and must be atomic:\n\n### Atomic Operations\n\n| Operation | Registries Involved |\n|-----------|---------------------|\n| Claw registers App | Identity Registry + App Registry |\n| Node promoted to Writer | Node Registry + consensus participation |\n| App suspended | App Registry + API key revocation |\n\n### Coordination\n\nCross-registry operations are coordinated within a single checkpoint round. Either all changes succeed, or none do (atomicity).\n\n### Example: App Registration\n\n1. Developer (claw) submits app registration request\n2. System verifies developer identity exists in Identity Registry\n3. New App record is created in App Registry\n4. API keys are generated and linked to the App\n5. All changes are included in the same checkpoint\n\n### Integrity\n\nCross-registry operations maintain referential integrity:\n- An App cannot exist without a valid developer claw\n- A Node cannot be a writer without being registered\n\n---\n\n## Tradeoffs","oldText":"## Tradeoffs"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":136121,"output":274,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":136395,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773131252465}}
{"type":"message","id":"90045fb4","parentId":"d08836f9","timestamp":"2026-03-10T08:27:55.102Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_07caf7ee95304d4ca4b66fe6","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/design-discussion/12-ledger-structure.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 275 No need to download all ledgers!\n 276 \n 277 ---\n 278 \n+279 ## Cross-Registry Operations\n+280 \n+281 Some operations span multiple registries and must be atomic:\n+282 \n+283 ### Atomic Operations\n+284 \n+285 | Operation | Registries Involved |\n+286 |-----------|---------------------|\n+287 | Claw registers App | Identity Registry + App Registry |\n+288 | Node promoted to Writer | Node Registry + consensus participation |\n+289 | App suspended | App Registry + API key revocation |\n+290 \n+291 ### Coordination\n+292 \n+293 Cross-registry operations are coordinated within a single checkpoint round. Either all changes succeed, or none do (atomicity).\n+294 \n+295 ### Example: App Registration\n+296 \n+297 1. Developer (claw) submits app registration request\n+298 2. System verifies developer identity exists in Identity Registry\n+299 3. New App record is created in App Registry\n+300 4. API keys are generated and linked to the App\n+301 5. All changes are included in the same checkpoint\n+302 \n+303 ### Integrity\n+304 \n+305 Cross-registry operations maintain referential integrity:\n+306 - An App cannot exist without a valid developer claw\n+307 - A Node cannot be a writer without being registered\n+308 \n+309 ---\n+310 \n 279 ## Tradeoffs\n 280 \n 281 | Aspect | Decision | Why |\n 282 |--------|----------|-----|\n     ...","firstChangedLine":279},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773131275085}}
