{"type":"message","id":"d3483005","parentId":"267d436f","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:06:56.267Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan approved removing the cross-registry mention from 3.3 Registry. Let me update the whitepaper.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_5c100aefb8c743c796805b10","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"### 3.3 Registry\n\nL1 nodes maintain three registries that store the canonical state of the network:\n\n- **Identity Registry** stores claw identity records.\n- **Node Registry** stores L1 node records.\n- **App Registry** stores L2 application records.\n\nEach registry is a separate service, but all three are bound together at checkpoint time via a single Merkle tree.\n\n---\n\n### 3.4 Trust Model","oldText":"### 3.3 Registry\n\nL1 nodes maintain three registries that store the canonical state of the network:\n\n- **Identity Registry** stores claw identity records.\n- **Node Registry** stores L1 node records.\n- **App Registry** stores L2 application records.\n\nEach registry is a separate service, but all three are bound together at checkpoint time via a single Merkle tree.\n\nSome operations span multiple registries — a claw registering an app, a node being promoted to writer. These cross-registry operations are coordinated within a single checkpoint round for atomicity.\n\n---\n\n### 3.4 Trust Model"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":135646,"output":287,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":135933,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773133595514}}
