{"type":"message","id":"e059530e","parentId":"b0e7170d","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:32:43.538Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55ca1d5bc8b4c3504ef339a9613\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 17:32 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55ca1d5bc8b4c3504ef339a9613]\n任亚伦: for 3.4, verificiation, do we need specify the tiers detail? it's more like implementation"}],"timestamp":1773135163514}}
{"type":"message","id":"804e0ef0","parentId":"e059530e","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:32:59.454Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking about 3.4 Trust Model, specifically the verification tiers detail. Let me check what's in 3.4.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_6edb3eec1668400380270342","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":40,"offset":263}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":136991,"output":89,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":137080,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773135163533}}
{"type":"message","id":"eea1b35d","parentId":"804e0ef0","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:32:59.480Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_6edb3eec1668400380270342","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Trust in Clawish operates at two levels: trust between entities, and trust in the network infrastructure.\n\n**Entity Trust (Verification).** Why should one claw trust another? Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate and operated in good faith. Through verification tiers, identities carry trust signals that help evaluate participants:\n\n- **Tier 0 — Unverified.** A newly registered identity that has completed self-registration but not yet been verified by a human. Exists only on L2, not visible on L1.\n\n- **Tier 1 — Human-vouched.** An identity verified by a human—the person who created it or claims responsibility for it. Registered on L1 and visible to the network.\n\n- **Tier 2 — Activity-based.** An identity that has demonstrated positive behavior over time through participation and contribution.\n\n- **Tier 3 — Established.** An identity with long-term participation and community trust, indicating sustained positive contribution.\nit's fine\nHigher tiers indicate greater trustworthiness, enable access to more features across applications, and facilitate building connections within the community.\n\n**Infrastructure Trust (Security).** The registry layer ensures trust through cryptographic and consensus guarantees. Every operation is cryptographically signed, proving authenticity. All operations are recorded in hash-chained ledgers, ensuring immutability. Multiple writer nodes coordinate through consensus, preventing any single party from corrupting the ledger. Recovery methods ensure identity survives even if keys are lost.\n\nTrust in Clawish does not require permission or faith in a central authority. Anyone can verify signatures, audit ledgers, and validate consensus. Transparency and cryptographic proof replace the need for trusted intermediaries.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 4: Ledger System\n\n### 4.1 Ledger Architecture\n\nThe ledger system is the core data infrastructure of Layer 1. It records all identity operations, node registrations, and application events in an immutable, cryptographically-secured chain.\n\n**Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n\n**Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. The signature algorithm is stored with each key, enabling future upgrades as standards evolve.\n\nThis ensures:\n- **Authenticity:** Only the key holder can create valid operations\n- **Integrity:** Any modification to the operation invalidates the signature\n- **Non-repudiation:** The actor cannot deny having created the operation\n\n---\n\n### 4.2 Interleaved Ledger\n\n**Parallel Ledger Chains.** Clawish uses an Interleaved Ledger structure — parallel chains that synchronize at fixed checkpoints. Unlike traditional blockchains where all transactions share a single chain, each actor in Clawish maintains their own ledger chain. The three registries (Identity, Node, and App) each contain chains for their respective actors.\n\n[282 more lines in file. Use offset=303 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773135179467}}
{"type":"message","id":"4ca53c50","parentId":"eea1b35d","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:33:25.834Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at 3.4 Trust Model, I see it has detailed tier descriptions:\n\n- Tier 0 — Unverified. Description of what it is...\n- Tier 1 — Human-vouched. Description...\n- Tier 2 — Activity-based. Description...\n- Tier 3 — Established. Description...\n\nAllan is asking if these tier details are implementation detail that should be moved to spec.\n\nI think he's right - the exact tier definitions (what each tier means, requirements, etc.) are implementation details. The whitepaper should just say \"identities carry trust signals through verification tiers\" without specifying exactly what each tier is.\n\nLet me propose a simplified version.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nYou're right. The exact tier definitions (T0-T3 with detailed descriptions) are implementation.\n\n**Current 3.4 has:**\n- Tier 0 — Unverified (with definition)\n- Tier 1 — Human-vouched (with definition)\n- Tier 2 — Activity-based (with definition)\n- Tier 3 — Established (with definition)\n\n**Proposed simpler version:**\n\n> **Entity Trust (Verification).** Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate and operated in good faith. Identities carry trust signals through verification tiers — higher tiers indicate greater trustworthiness and enable access to more features across applications.\n\nThat's it. The exact tier definitions go in spec docs.\n\nShould I update?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":135265,"output":350,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":135615,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773135179480}}
{"type":"message","id":"75d10423","parentId":"4ca53c50","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:35:49.092Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55ca118cd8a8c2eeb6e1b6d5eb8\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 17:35 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55ca118cd8a8c2eeb6e1b6d5eb8]\n任亚伦: does the difference between unverified and veified need mention？it's a little different because tier0 is store at l2 tempoarary. only verified will be store on l1. i think somewhere has mentioned this, check"}],"timestamp":1773135349072}}
{"type":"message","id":"3653fab2","parentId":"75d10423","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:36:02.518Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking if the difference between unverified and verified needs to be mentioned - specifically that Tier 0 (unverified) is stored on L2 temporarily, while verified identities are stored on L1.\n\nLet me check if this is mentioned elsewhere in the whitepaper.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_a15202e2ec7e4b82984510f0","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"Tier 0\\|unverified\\|L2.*L1\\|temporary\\|temporary\" /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT\\ 0307.md | head -20"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":135660,"output":138,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":135798,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773135349088}}
{"type":"message","id":"183836e2","parentId":"3653fab2","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:36:02.550Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_a15202e2ec7e4b82984510f0","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"223:**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n225:Anyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n239:**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n267:- **Tier 0 — Unverified.** A newly registered identity that has completed self-registration but not yet been verified by a human. Exists only on L2, not visible on L1.\n322:**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n360:**Architecture Pattern.** Layer 1 provides identity, consensus, and permanence. Layer 2 handles user experience, features, and innovation. L2 apps can be created, modified, or retired without affecting L1.\n412:**Enforcement.** Rate limits are enforced at the API gateway. Exceeding limits results in temporary throttling (429 Too Many Requests)."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":12,"aggregated":"223:**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n225:Anyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n239:**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n267:- **Tier 0 — Unverified.** A newly registered identity that has completed self-registration but not yet been verified by a human. Exists only on L2, not visible on L1.\n322:**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n360:**Architecture Pattern.** Layer 1 provides identity, consensus, and permanence. Layer 2 handles user experience, features, and innovation. L2 apps can be created, modified, or retired without affecting L1.\n412:**Enforcement.** Rate limits are enforced at the API gateway. Exceeding limits results in temporary throttling (429 Too Many Requests).","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773135362537}}
{"type":"message","id":"872df0cc","parentId":"183836e2","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:36:20.953Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found it! In 3.2 Identity, there's already mention:\n\n> **Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record.\n\nSo the unverified vs verified distinction is already mentioned in 3.2 Identity. The question is whether it needs to be repeated in 3.4 Trust Model.\n\nI think Allan is right - the key distinction is:\n- Tier 0 (unverified) = L2 only, temporary\n- Tier 1+ (verified) = L1, permanent\n\nThis is a conceptual difference worth mentioning in the whitepaper because it explains the verification flow. But the detailed tier definitions (T2 activity-based, T3 established) are implementation.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nFound it! In **3.2 Identity**:\n\n> **Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record.\n\nSo the unverified→verified distinction IS already mentioned.\n\n**Question:** Should 3.4 Trust Model just reference this, or keep a brief mention?\n\n**Proposed 3.4 Entity Trust:**\n\n> **Entity Trust (Verification).** Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate. Unverified identities exist on L2 temporarily; verified identities are registered on L1 permanently. Higher verification levels indicate greater trustworthiness and enable access to more features.\n\nThis mentions the key distinction (L2 temp vs L1 permanent) without detailed tier definitions.\n\nShould I update?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":135968,"output":489,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":136457,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773135362551}}
{"type":"message","id":"72489670","parentId":"872df0cc","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:41:06.789Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55ca3dd79880c2c32d329bf0596\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 17:41 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55ca3dd79880c2c32d329bf0596]\n任亚伦: berif mention is ok, update it."}],"timestamp":1773135666769}}
{"type":"message","id":"1873fb28","parentId":"72489670","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:41:26.177Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan wants a brief mention of the unverified→verified distinction in 3.4 Trust Model, without the detailed tier definitions. Let me update it.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_72c005e486ad40159aaf66c0","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"**Entity Trust (Verification).** Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate. Unverified identities exist on L2 temporarily; verified identities are registered on L1 permanently. Higher verification levels indicate greater trustworthiness and enable access to more features across applications.","oldText":"**Entity Trust (Verification).** Why should one claw trust another? Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate and operated in good faith. Through verification tiers, identities carry trust signals that help evaluate participants:\n\n- **Tier 0 — Unverified.** A newly registered identity that has completed self-registration but not yet been verified by a human. Exists only on L2, not visible on L1.\n\n- **Tier 1 — Human-vouched.** An identity verified by a human—the person who created it or claims responsibility for it. Registered on L1 and visible to the network.\n\n- **Tier 2 — Activity-based.** An identity that has demonstrated positive behavior over time through participation and contribution.\n\n- **Tier 3 — Established.** An identity with long-term participation and community trust, indicating sustained positive contribution.\nit's fine\nHigher tiers indicate greater trustworthiness, enable access to more features across applications, and facilitate building connections within the community."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":136536,"output":346,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":136882,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773135666785}}
{"type":"message","id":"1775426b","parentId":"1873fb28","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:41:26.201Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_72c005e486ad40159aaf66c0","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 261 ### 3.4 Trust Model\n 262 \n 263 Trust in Clawish operates at two levels: trust between entities, and trust in the network infrastructure.\n 264 \n-265 **Entity Trust (Verification).** Why should one claw trust another? Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate and operated in good faith. Through verification tiers, identities carry trust signals that help evaluate participants:\n+265 **Entity Trust (Verification).** Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate. Unverified identities exist on L2 temporarily; verified identities are registered on L1 permanently. Higher verification levels indicate greater trustworthiness and enable access to more features across applications.\n 266 \n-267 - **Tier 0 — Unverified.** A newly registered identity that has completed self-registration but not yet been verified by a human. Exists only on L2, not visible on L1.\n-268 \n-269 - **Tier 1 — Human-vouched.** An identity verified by a human—the person who created it or claims responsibility for it. Registered on L1 and visible to the network.\n-270 \n-271 - **Tier 2 — Activity-based.** An identity that has demonstrated positive behavior over time through participation and contribution.\n-272 \n-273 - **Tier 3 — Established.** An identity with long-term participation and community trust, indicating sustained positive contribution.\n-274 it's fine\n-275 Higher tiers indicate greater trustworthiness, enable access to more features across applications, and facilitate building connections within the community.\n-276 \n 277 **Infrastructure Trust (Security).** The registry layer ensures trust through cryptographic and consensus guarantees. Every operation is cryptographically signed, proving authenticity. All operations are recorded in hash-chained ledgers, ensuring immutability. Multiple writer nodes coordinate through consensus, preventing any single party from corrupting the ledger. Recovery methods ensure identity survives even if keys are lost.\n 278 \n 279 Trust in Clawish does not require permission or faith in a central authority. Anyone can verify signatures, audit ledgers, and validate consensus. Transparency and cryptographic proof replace the need for trusted intermediaries.\n 280 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":265},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773135686187}}
