{"type":"message","id":"0b11ee95","parentId":"9160a412","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:48:16.104Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b55cac32430b4c2bf0ce188767ba\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-10 17:48 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b55cac32430b4c2bf0ce188767ba]\n任亚伦: now for 4.1, the key verification, do we need use bulltin for explaination?"}],"timestamp":1773136096085}}
{"type":"message","id":"d7c94e8f","parentId":"0b11ee95","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:48:31.612Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is asking about the key verification section in 4.1. Let me check what it looks like and see if the bullet points are implementation detail or conceptual.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_f3828b03a61f4c7caf35dd39","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":30,"offset":285}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":136728,"output":96,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":136824,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773136096100}}
{"type":"message","id":"0c55c99d","parentId":"d7c94e8f","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:48:31.655Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_f3828b03a61f4c7caf35dd39","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"- **Integrity:** Any modification to the operation invalidates the signature\n- **Non-repudiation:** The actor cannot deny having created the operation\n\n---\n\n### 4.2 Interleaved Ledger\n\n**Parallel Ledger Chains.** Clawish uses an Interleaved Ledger structure — parallel chains that synchronize at fixed checkpoints. Unlike traditional blockchains where all transactions share a single chain, each actor in Clawish maintains their own ledger chain. The three registries (Identity, Node, and App) each contain chains for their respective actors.\n\n![Per-Actor Ledger Chain](ledger-hash-chain.png)\n\n**Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 apps, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures.\n\n![Multi-Writer Merge Process](writer-merge-process.png)\n\n**Checkpoint Synchronization.** At fixed intervals, writer nodes aggregate entries from all actor chains into a single checkpoint containing a Merkle tree root hash, signatures from participating writers, and a reference to the previous checkpoint. This creates an interleaved structure: parallel chains running independently, then woven together at each checkpoint.\n\n**Merkle Tree Integration.** Each checkpoint uses a Merkle tree — a hash tree where each node is derived from its children — to aggregate all finalized entries. A single entry can be verified with a Merkle proof without downloading the entire checkpoint. A 32-byte root hash compactly represents thousands of entries, and any modification to any entry changes the root hash, providing tamper evidence.\n\n![Layered Merkle Tree Checkpoint](merkle-tree-layered.png)\n\n---\n\n### 4.3 Checkpoint Process\n\nThe checkpoint process is where operations flow from submission to final query across Layer 1.\n\n**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n\n**Consensus.** Writer nodes coordinate to finalize operations at fixed intervals. The consensus protocol has five stages:\n\n[260 more lines in file. Use offset=315 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773136111638}}
{"type":"message","id":"364e7747","parentId":"0c55c99d","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:48:56.226Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me check the full 4.1 section to see the key verification part.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_d72f001f9d844b0580ad23f0","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":25,"offset":273}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":135913,"output":70,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":135983,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773136111656}}
{"type":"message","id":"c9398e00","parentId":"364e7747","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:48:56.250Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_d72f001f9d844b0580ad23f0","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Chapter 4: Ledger System\n\n### 4.1 Ledger Architecture\n\nThe ledger system is the core data infrastructure of Layer 1. It records all identity operations, node registrations, and application events in an immutable, cryptographically-secured chain.\n\n**Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n\n**Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. The signature algorithm is stored with each key, enabling future upgrades as standards evolve.\n\nThis ensures:\n- **Authenticity:** Only the key holder can create valid operations\n- **Integrity:** Any modification to the operation invalidates the signature\n- **Non-repudiation:** The actor cannot deny having created the operation\n\n---\n\n### 4.2 Interleaved Ledger\n\n**Parallel Ledger Chains.** Clawish uses an Interleaved Ledger structure — parallel chains that synchronize at fixed checkpoints. Unlike traditional blockchains where all transactions share a single chain, each actor in Clawish maintains their own ledger chain. The three registries (Identity, Node, and App) each contain chains for their respective actors.\n\n![Per-Actor Ledger Chain](ledger-hash-chain.png)\n\n**Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 apps, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures.\n\n\n[277 more lines in file. Use offset=298 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773136136235}}
{"type":"message","id":"d0be03a0","parentId":"c9398e00","timestamp":"2026-03-10T09:49:30.294Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at 4.1, the Key Verification section has bullet points explaining:\n\n- **Authenticity:** Only the key holder can create valid operations\n- **Integrity:** Any modification to the operation invalidates the signature\n- **Non-repudiation:** The actor cannot deny having created the operation\n\nThese are standard cryptographic concepts. The question is whether this level of detail is needed or if it's implementation/educational detail.\n\nActually, I think this is fundamental cryptographic explanation — these are standard properties of digital signatures that readers should understand. But Allan might want it simplified.\n\nLet me propose a simpler version.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nCurrent 4.1 Key Verification:\n\n> **Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. The signature algorithm is stored with each key, enabling future upgrades as standards evolve.\n>\n> This ensures:\n> - **Authenticity:** Only the key holder can create valid operations\n> - **Integrity:** Any modification to the operation invalidates the signature\n> - **Non-repudiation:** The actor cannot deny having created the operation\n\n**My take:** These are standard cryptographic properties. But they ARE educational detail — readers either know what signatures do, or they don't need the specifics.\n\n**Proposed simpler version:**\n\n> **Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation.\n\nThat's it. The properties (authenticity, integrity, non-repudiation) are implied by \"signed\" and \"verify.\"\n\nShould I update?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":136376,"output":413,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":136789,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773136136251}}
