{"type":"message","id":"eb06bd3b","parentId":"fef3620e","timestamp":"2026-03-10T11:12:03.139Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is right. The algorithm tag stored with the key is for verification purposes - so that when verifying a signature, you know which algorithm to use. It's not specifically for \"future upgrades\" - that's just a side benefit.\n\nThe real purpose is: when verifying a signature, you need to know which algorithm was used. Different keys might use different algorithms.\n\nLet me think about how to rephrase this more accurately.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]]\n\nYou're right. The algorithm tag is for verification — so the system knows which algorithm to use when verifying a signature. Different keys can use different algorithms.\n\n**Simpler version:**\n\n> **Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. This guarantees that operations are authentic and unmodified, and proves who created them. The signature algorithm is stored with each key to enable correct verification.\n\nOr even simpler — remove it entirely since it's an implementation detail:\n\n> **Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. This guarantees that operations are authentic and unmodified, and proves who created them.\n\nWhich do you prefer?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":138294,"output":304,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":138598,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773141050822}}
{"type":"message","id":"6ff58820","parentId":"eb06bd3b","timestamp":"2026-03-10T11:12:03.935Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You're right. The algorithm tag is for verification — so the system knows which algorithm to use when verifying a signature. Different keys can use different algorithms.\n\n**Simpler version:**\n\n> **Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. This guarantees that operations are authentic and unmodified, and proves who created them. The signature algorithm is stored with each key to enable correct verification.\n\nOr even simpler — remove it entirely since it's an implementation detail:\n\n> **Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. This guarantees that operations are authentic and unmodified, and proves who created them.\n\nWhich do you prefer?"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773141123935}}
