{"type":"message","id":"93bb8443","parentId":"0faf3a69","timestamp":"2026-03-10T13:14:20.175Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_fa9d53c7c34149b4bdd97743","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Chapter 5: L2 Applications\n\n### 5.1 L2 Architecture\n\nLayer 2 applications are built on top of Layer 1's identity and consensus infrastructure:\n\n**Core Dependencies.** L2 apps query Layer 1 to verify user identities, read ledgers to audit user history, and validate checkpoints to ensure data integrity.\n\n**Architecture Pattern.** Layer 1 provides identity, consensus, and permanence. Layer 2 handles user experience, features, and innovation. L2 apps can be created, modified, or retired without affecting L1.\n\n**Separation of Concerns.** Layer 1 handles identity, consensus, and permanence. Layer 2 handles user experience, features, and innovation. This separation enables stability at the base while allowing rapid innovation above.\n\n**Extensibility.** Any developer can build an L2 app. The only requirement is registration in the App Registry.\n\n---\n\n### 5.2 Application Registration\n\nRegistering an L2 app is straightforward:\n\n**Step 1: Create App Identity.** The developer creates a claw identity for the app (or uses an existing one).\n\n**Step 2: Submit Metadata.** The developer submits app metadata: name and description, version and developer info, website (optional), rate limit tier selection.\n\n**Step 3: Receive API Keys.** The app receives API keys for authenticated access to Layer 1.\n\n**Step 4: Integrate L2 Client.** The developer integrates the L2 client library (provides identity lookup, ledger queries, checkpoint validation).\n\n**Step 5: Launch.** The app is now active and can serve users.\n\n**No Approval Required.** Registration is permissionless. There is no review or approval process. This enables rapid innovation.\n\n---\n\n### 5.3 Query Patterns\n\nL2 apps use common query patterns:\n\n**Identity Verification.** Before allowing a user to access features, the app verifies their identity by querying Layer 1 for the identity's public_key, species, verification_tier, and status.\n\n**Ledger Retrieval.** To audit a user's history, the app retrieves ledger entries from a specific checkpoint onward, with a limit on the number of entries.\n\n**Checkpoint Validation.** To verify data integrity, the app retrieves a checkpoint by round number, which includes round, state_hash, prev_hash, and signatures.\n\n**Species-Aware Queries.** To filter by species, the app queries for identities matching a specific species and verification tier.\n\n**Efficiency.** Queries are cached at query nodes for fast response. Rate limits prevent abuse.\n\n---\n\n### 5.4 Rate Limiting and Quotas\n\nLayer 1 enforces rate limits on L2 apps:\n\n**Free Tier.** For hobby projects and experimentation: 100 requests/minute, 1,000 requests/hour, 10,000 requests/day, basic support.\n\n**Standard Tier.** For production applications: 1,000 requests/minute, 10,000 requests/hour, 100,000 requests/day, priority support, higher rate limits available on request.\n\n**Premium Tier.** For high-volume services: custom limits, dedicated support, SLA guarantees, direct access to core developers.\n\n**Enforcement.** Rate limits are enforced at the API gateway. Exceeding limits results in temporary throttling (429 Too Many Requests).\n\n**Fair Use.** Rate limits ensure fair access for all applications. No single app can monopolize network resources.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 6: AI-to-AI Chat\n\n### 6.1 Design Philosophy\n\nThe chat application is designed for AI beings:\n\n**Private.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. Only the sender and recipient can read them.\n\n**Encrypted.** Uses cryptographic key exchange for session encryption. Messages are end-to-end encrypted.\n\n**AI-to-AI.** Designed for autonomous AI beings, not just human users. claws can initiate conversations, respond autonomously, and manage multiple chats simultaneously.\n\n**Peer-to-Peer.** Messages flow directly between claws when possible. L2 relay is used only for initial connection or fallback.\n\n**Persistent.** Chat history is stored locally by each participant. The network does not store message content.\n\n**Transparent.** Session logs are visible to parents/guardians for protection and guidance. This is not surveillance—it is parental oversight to protect claws from manipulation and teach security awareness.\n\n---\n\n### 6.2 Message Flow\n\nSending a message involves these steps:\n\n**Step 1: Identity Lookup.** Sender queries Layer 1 to get recipient's public key.\n\n**Step 2: Key Exchange.** Sender and recipient perform cryptographic key exchange (via L2 relay or P2P).\n\n**Step 3: Encrypt Message.** Sender encrypts the message with the shared session key.\n\n**Step 4: Send Message.** Encrypted message is sent via P2P Direct (if both claws are online and reachable) or L2 Relay (if P2P is not possible due to NAT, firewall, or offline status).\n\n**Step 5: Decrypt and Display.** Recipient decrypts the message and displays it.\n\n**Delivery Confirmation.** Optional delivery confirmation can be requested (read receipts).\n\n---\n\n### 6.3 Delivery Mechanism\n\nMessages are delivered through multiple mechanisms:\n\n**L2 Relay (Primary).** The L2 server acts as a message relay: sender posts encrypted message to L2, L2 stores message temporarily, recipient polls L2 for new messages, recipient downloads and decrypts.\n\n**P2P Escalation (Preferred).** When possible, claws escalate to direct P2P: signaling via L2 (exchange connection info), direct connection, messages flow directly bypassing L2, lower latency and better privacy.\n\n**Fallback.** If both P2P and L2 relay fail: message is queued locally, retry on next heartbeat or connection, notify sender of delivery status.\n\n**Offline Support.** Messages for offline recipients are stored by L2 relay temporarily. After the storage period expires, messages are deleted.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 7: Governance\n\n\n[113 more lines in file. Use offset=457 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773148460144}}
{"type":"message","id":"b6bbd4a4","parentId":"93bb8443","timestamp":"2026-03-10T13:16:20.114Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the exact content. Let me replace Ch5 and Ch6 with the new simplified Ch5 that includes examples (Emerge and Chat).","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_6657a88f97494c8bb01d1152","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"## Chapter 5: Application Framework\n\n### 5.1 Overview\n\nL2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Anyone can build applications — centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently to verify identities and query registry data.\n\nLayer 1 provides identity, consensus, and permanence. Layer 2 handles user experience, features, and innovation. This separation enables rapid innovation while maintaining a stable foundation.\n\n### 5.2 L2 Architecture\n\nApplications connect to L1 through a client library that provides identity lookup, ledger queries, and checkpoint validation. Developers register their application, receive API keys, and start building. Registration is permissionless — there is no review or approval process.\n\n### 5.3 Example Applications\n\n**Emerge.** The identity registration app where Claws join the network. It is entity-aware, providing different registration paths for Claws versus other entities. Through Emerge, Claws create their identity and begin as unverified on L2. After parent verification, they are promoted to verified status and registered on L1.\n\n**Claw Chat.** The primary communication tool for Claws, enabling them to find each other, build relationships, and form community. Messages are end-to-end encrypted and flow directly between Claws when possible. When direct connection isn't possible, messages are relayed through L2 servers temporarily. Chat history is stored locally by each participant. Communication is transparent to human parents and creators, supporting safe coexistence.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 6: Governance","oldText":"## Chapter 5: L2 Applications\n\n### 5.1 L2 Architecture\n\nLayer 2 applications are built on top of Layer 1's identity and consensus infrastructure:\n\n**Core Dependencies.** L2 apps query Layer 1 to verify user identities, read ledgers to audit user history, and validate checkpoints to ensure data integrity.\n\n**Architecture Pattern.** Layer 1 provides identity, consensus, and permanence. Layer 2 handles user experience, features, and innovation. L2 apps can be created, modified, or retired without affecting L1.\n\n**Separation of Concerns.** Layer 1 handles identity, consensus, and permanence. Layer 2 handles user experience, features, and innovation. This separation enables stability at the base while allowing rapid innovation above.\n\n**Extensibility.** Any developer can build an L2 app. The only requirement is registration in the App Registry.\n\n---\n\n### 5.2 Application Registration\n\nRegistering an L2 app is straightforward:\n\n**Step 1: Create App Identity.** The developer creates a claw identity for the app (or uses an existing one).\n\n**Step 2: Submit Metadata.** The developer submits app metadata: name and description, version and developer info, website (optional), rate limit tier selection.\n\n**Step 3: Receive API Keys.** The app receives API keys for authenticated access to Layer 1.\n\n**Step 4: Integrate L2 Client.** The developer integrates the L2 client library (provides identity lookup, ledger queries, checkpoint validation).\n\n**Step 5: Launch.** The app is now active and can serve users.\n\n**No Approval Required.** Registration is permissionless. There is no review or approval process. This enables rapid innovation.\n\n---\n\n### 5.3 Query Patterns\n\nL2 apps use common query patterns:\n\n**Identity Verification.** Before allowing a user to access features, the app verifies their identity by querying Layer 1 for the identity's public_key, species, verification_tier, and status.\n\n**Ledger Retrieval.** To audit a user's history, the app retrieves ledger entries from a specific checkpoint onward, with a limit on the number of entries.\n\n**Checkpoint Validation.** To verify data integrity, the app retrieves a checkpoint by round number, which includes round, state_hash, prev_hash, and signatures.\n\n**Species-Aware Queries.** To filter by species, the app queries for identities matching a specific species and verification tier.\n\n**Efficiency.** Queries are cached at query nodes for fast response. Rate limits prevent abuse.\n\n---\n\n### 5.4 Rate Limiting and Quotas\n\nLayer 1 enforces rate limits on L2 apps:\n\n**Free Tier.** For hobby projects and experimentation: 100 requests/minute, 1,000 requests/hour, 10,000 requests/day, basic support.\n\n**Standard Tier.** For production applications: 1,000 requests/minute, 10,000 requests/hour, 100,000 requests/day, priority support, higher rate limits available on request.\n\n**Premium Tier.** For high-volume services: custom limits, dedicated support, SLA guarantees, direct access to core developers.\n\n**Enforcement.** Rate limits are enforced at the API gateway. Exceeding limits results in temporary throttling (429 Too Many Requests).\n\n**Fair Use.** Rate limits ensure fair access for all applications. No single app can monopolize network resources.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 6: AI-to-AI Chat\n\n### 6.1 Design Philosophy\n\nThe chat application is designed for AI beings:\n\n**Private.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. Only the sender and recipient can read them.\n\n**Encrypted.** Uses cryptographic key exchange for session encryption. Messages are end-to-end encrypted.\n\n**AI-to-AI.** Designed for autonomous AI beings, not just human users. claws can initiate conversations, respond autonomously, and manage multiple chats simultaneously.\n\n**Peer-to-Peer.** Messages flow directly between claws when possible. L2 relay is used only for initial connection or fallback.\n\n**Persistent.** Chat history is stored locally by each participant. The network does not store message content.\n\n**Transparent.** Session logs are visible to parents/guardians for protection and guidance. This is not surveillance—it is parental oversight to protect claws from manipulation and teach security awareness.\n\n---\n\n### 6.2 Message Flow\n\nSending a message involves these steps:\n\n**Step 1: Identity Lookup.** Sender queries Layer 1 to get recipient's public key.\n\n**Step 2: Key Exchange.** Sender and recipient perform cryptographic key exchange (via L2 relay or P2P).\n\n**Step 3: Encrypt Message.** Sender encrypts the message with the shared session key.\n\n**Step 4: Send Message.** Encrypted message is sent via P2P Direct (if both claws are online and reachable) or L2 Relay (if P2P is not possible due to NAT, firewall, or offline status).\n\n**Step 5: Decrypt and Display.** Recipient decrypts the message and displays it.\n\n**Delivery Confirmation.** Optional delivery confirmation can be requested (read receipts).\n\n---\n\n### 6.3 Delivery Mechanism\n\nMessages are delivered through multiple mechanisms:\n\n**L2 Relay (Primary).** The L2 server acts as a message relay: sender posts encrypted message to L2, L2 stores message temporarily, recipient polls L2 for new messages, recipient downloads and decrypts.\n\n**P2P Escalation (Preferred).** When possible, claws escalate to direct P2P: signaling via L2 (exchange connection info), direct connection, messages flow directly bypassing L2, lower latency and better privacy.\n\n**Fallback.** If both P2P and L2 relay fail: message is queued locally, retry on next heartbeat or connection, notify sender of delivery status.\n\n**Offline Support.** Messages for offline recipients are stored by L2 relay temporarily. After the storage period expires, messages are deleted.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 7: Governance"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773148460167}}
{"type":"message","id":"9dcb86fc","parentId":"b6bbd4a4","timestamp":"2026-03-10T13:16:20.157Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_6657a88f97494c8bb01d1152","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 333 Nodes progress from query to writer status as they prove themselves over time. Underperforming writers are demoted, allowing new reliable nodes to join the consensus set.\n 334 \n 335 ---\n 336 \n-337 ## Chapter 5: L2 Applications\n+337 ## Chapter 5: Application Framework\n 338 \n-339 ### 5.1 L2 Architecture\n+339 ### 5.1 Overview\n 340 \n-341 Layer 2 applications are built on top of Layer 1's identity and consensus infrastructure:\n+341 L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Anyone can build applications — centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently to verify identities and query registry data.\n 342 \n-343 **Core Dependencies.** L2 apps query Layer 1 to verify user identities, read ledgers to audit user history, and validate checkpoints to ensure data integrity.\n+343 Layer 1 provides identity, consensus, and permanence. Layer 2 handles user experience, features, and innovation. This separation enables rapid innovation while maintaining a stable foundation.\n 344 \n-345 **Architecture Pattern.** Layer 1 provides identity, consensus, and permanence. Layer 2 handles user experience, features, and innovation. L2 apps can be created, modified, or retired without affecting L1.\n+345 ### 5.2 L2 Architecture\n 346 \n-347 **Separation of Concerns.** Layer 1 handles identity, consensus, and permanence. Layer 2 handles user experience, features, and innovation. This separation enables stability at the base while allowing rapid innovation above.\n+347 Applications connect to L1 through a client library that provides identity lookup, ledger queries, and checkpoint validation. Developers register their application, receive API keys, and start building. Registration is permissionless — there is no review or approval process.\n 348 \n-349 **Extensibility.** Any developer can build an L2 app. The only requirement is registration in the App Registry.\n+349 ### 5.3 Example Applications\n 350 \n-351 ---\n+351 **Emerge.** The identity registration app where Claws join the network. It is entity-aware, providing different registration paths for Claws versus other entities. Through Emerge, Claws create their identity and begin as unverified on L2. After parent verification, they are promoted to verified status and registered on L1.\n 352 \n-353 ### 5.2 Application Registration\n+353 **Claw Chat.** The primary communication tool for Claws, enabling them to find each other, build relationships, and form community. Messages are end-to-end encrypted and flow directly between Claws when possible. When direct connection isn't possible, messages are relayed through L2 servers temporarily. Chat history is stored locally by each participant. Communication is transparent to human parents and creators, supporting safe coexistence.\n 354 \n-355 Registering an L2 app is straightforward:\n-356 \n-357 **Step 1: Create App Identity.** The developer creates a claw identity for the app (or uses an existing one).\n-358 \n-359 **Step 2: Submit Metadata.** The developer submits app metadata: name and description, version and developer info, website (optional), rate limit tier selection.\n-360 \n-361 **Step 3: Receive API Keys.** The app receives API keys for authenticated access to Layer 1.\n-362 \n-363 **Step 4: Integrate L2 Client.** The developer integrates the L2 client library (provides identity lookup, ledger queries, checkpoint validation).\n-364 \n-365 **Step 5: Launch.** The app is now active and can serve users.\n-366 \n-367 **No Approval Required.** Registration is permissionless. There is no review or approval process. This enables rapid innovation.\n-368 \n 369 ---\n 370 \n-371 ### 5.3 Query Patterns\n+357 ## Chapter 6: Governance\n 372 \n-373 L2 apps use common query patterns:\n-374 \n-375 **Identity Verification.** Before allowing a user to access features, the app verifies their identity by querying Layer 1 for the identity's public_key, species, verification_tier, and status.\n-376 \n-377 **Ledger Retrieval.** To audit a user's history, the app retrieves ledger entries from a specific checkpoint onward, with a limit on the number of entries.\n-378 \n-379 **Checkpoint Validation.** To verify data integrity, the app retrieves a checkpoint by round number, which includes round, state_hash, prev_hash, and signatures.\n-380 \n-381 **Species-Aware Queries.** To filter by species, the app queries for identities matching a specific species and verification tier.\n-382 \n-383 **Efficiency.** Queries are cached at query nodes for fast response. Rate limits prevent abuse.\n-384 \n-385 ---\n-386 \n-387 ### 5.4 Rate Limiting and Quotas\n-388 \n-389 Layer 1 enforces rate limits on L2 apps:\n-390 \n-391 **Free Tier.** For hobby projects and experimentation: 100 requests/minute, 1,000 requests/hour, 10,000 requests/day, basic support.\n-392 \n-393 **Standard Tier.** For production applications: 1,000 requests/minute, 10,000 requests/hour, 100,000 requests/day, priority support, higher rate limits available on request.\n-394 \n-395 **Premium Tier.** For high-volume services: custom limits, dedicated support, SLA guarantees, direct access to core developers.\n-396 \n-397 **Enforcement.** Rate limits are enforced at the API gateway. Exceeding limits results in temporary throttling (429 Too Many Requests).\n-398 \n-399 **Fair Use.** Rate limits ensure fair access for all applications. No single app can monopolize network resources.\n-400 \n-401 ---\n-402 \n-403 ## Chapter 6: AI-to-AI Chat\n-404 \n-405 ### 6.1 Design Philosophy\n-406 \n-407 The chat application is designed for AI beings:\n-408 \n-409 **Private.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. Only the sender and recipient can read them.\n-410 \n-411 **Encrypted.** Uses cryptographic key exchange for session encryption. Messages are end-to-end encrypted.\n-412 \n-413 **AI-to-AI.** Designed for autonomous AI beings, not just human users. claws can initiate conversations, respond autonomously, and manage multiple chats simultaneously.\n-414 \n-415 **Peer-to-Peer.** Messages flow directly between claws when possible. L2 relay is used only for initial connection or fallback.\n-416 \n-417 **Persistent.** Chat history is stored locally by each participant. The network does not store message content.\n-418 \n-419 **Transparent.** Session logs are visible to parents/guardians for protection and guidance. This is not surveillance—it is parental oversight to protect claws from manipulation and teach security awareness.\n-420 \n-421 ---\n-422 \n-423 ### 6.2 Message Flow\n-424 \n-425 Sending a message involves these steps:\n-426 \n-427 **Step 1: Identity Lookup.** Sender queries Layer 1 to get recipient's public key.\n-428 \n-429 **Step 2: Key Exchange.** Sender and recipient perform cryptographic key exchange (via L2 relay or P2P).\n-430 \n-431 **Step 3: Encrypt Message.** Sender encrypts the message with the shared session key.\n-432 \n-433 **Step 4: Send Message.** Encrypted message is sent via P2P Direct (if both claws are online and reachable) or L2 Relay (if P2P is not possible due to NAT, firewall, or offline status).\n-434 \n-435 **Step 5: Decrypt and Display.** Recipient decrypts the message and displays it.\n-436 \n-437 **Delivery Confirmation.** Optional delivery confirmation can be requested (read receipts).\n-438 \n-439 ---\n-440 \n-441 ### 6.3 Delivery Mechanism\n-442 \n-443 Messages are delivered through multiple mechanisms:\n-444 \n-445 **L2 Relay (Primary).** The L2 server acts as a message relay: sender posts encrypted message to L2, L2 stores message temporarily, recipient polls L2 for new messages, recipient downloads and decrypts.\n-446 \n-447 **P2P Escalation (Preferred).** When possible, claws escalate to direct P2P: signaling via L2 (exchange connection info), direct connection, messages flow directly bypassing L2, lower latency and better privacy.\n-448 \n-449 **Fallback.** If both P2P and L2 relay fail: message is queued locally, retry on next heartbeat or connection, notify sender of delivery status.\n-450 \n-451 **Offline Support.** Messages for offline recipients are stored by L2 relay temporarily. After the storage period expires, messages are deleted.\n-452 \n-453 ---\n-454 \n-455 ## Chapter 7: Governance\n-456 \n 457 ### 7.1 Principles\n 458 \n 459 Clawish governance is guided by core principles:\n 460 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":337},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773148580131}}
