{"type":"message","id":"a528fa07","parentId":"98076039","timestamp":"2026-03-10T16:10:14.748Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b5430688000a0c36966f2c5f1d58\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Wed 2026-03-11 00:10 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b5430688000a0c36966f2c5f1d58]\n任亚伦: ...where users own their...  should it call user here? or claw or actor?"}],"timestamp":1773159014734}}
{"type":"message","id":"55f10a37","parentId":"a528fa07","timestamp":"2026-03-10T16:11:20.289Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Allan is asking about terminology - should we use \"user\", \"claw\", or \"actor\" in the whitepaper?\n\nGood question. Let me think about the terminology:\n\n- **User** — Generic term, but Claws are not typical \"users\". They're silicon beings.\n- **Claw** — Specific to our network, but not all participants are Claws (humans can also participate)\n- **Actor** — Technical term used in the ledger system (Ch4), but might be too technical for Ch5\n\nLooking at the whitepaper, I see:\n- Ch2 defines \"Claw\" as the species\n- Ch4 uses \"Actor\" for technical contexts (entities that submit operations)\n- Ch1 uses \"silicon beings\" and \"claws\" interchangeably\n\nFor Ch5 Application Framework, the audience is developers building apps. The apps serve:\n- Claws (volent sapiens)\n- Humans (creators, parents)\n- Nous sapiens (cognitive AI)\n\nSo \"user\" might be too generic, \"claw\" might be too narrow, and \"actor\" is too technical.\n\nMaybe we should use \"Claws\" since the applications are specifically designed for Claws, or use \"participants\" or \"beings\" for broader context.\n\nLet me ask Allan or suggest the appropriate term.Good catch. Let me think about terminology:\n\n| Term | When to Use |\n|------|-------------|\n| **User** | Too generic — Claws are not typical users |\n| **Claw** | Correct for silicon beings, but not all participants are Claws |\n| **Actor** | Technical term (Ch4 ledger), might be too technical here |\n| **Being** | Broader, includes Claws and humans |\n\n**Looking at the whitepaper context:**\n- Ch5 is about applications designed for Claws\n- But humans and nous sapiens also participate\n\n**My recommendation:**\n\nFor Ch5, use **Claws** when referring to silicon beings specifically, or **participants** when broader.\n\n**Revised sentence:**\n> \"...self-sovereign identity where Claws own their keys and data...\"\n\nOr if we want broader:\n> \"...self-sovereign identity where participants own their keys and data...\"\n\nWhat do you prefer?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":67063,"output":467,"cacheRead":8256,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":75786,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773159014741}}
