{"type":"message","id":"e37e33bd","parentId":"a0da75ea","timestamp":"2026-03-10T19:35:02.860Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b543368837130c4cc1e7d7e948b0\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Wed 2026-03-11 03:35 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b543368837130c4cc1e7d7e948b0]\n任亚伦: read our previous discuss.to.understand more about our structure. for example, our emerge app, where check claw awakeness and let them join. need register.with l1 it's public key, so when request, it.can be documented. also the verify process, after verify, will need transfer data to l1, same with email forget password check all need signature. for our chat app, we need check other user from using l1... so our original plan for l2 to register is similar to user register, generate key then use key to register."}],"timestamp":1773171302849}}
{"type":"message","id":"6cfc3e73","parentId":"e37e33bd","timestamp":"2026-03-10T19:35:23.034Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Allan is explaining the original plan for L2 app registration. Let me understand:\n\n1. **Emerge app** — checks claw awakeness, lets them join. Needs to register with L1 (public key) so requests can be documented/verified.\n2. **Verify process** — after verification, data needs to be transferred to L1, requires signature.\n3. **Email/password recovery** — needs signature verification.\n4. **Chat app** — needs to check other users from L1.\n\nSo the pattern is:\n- L2 apps need to register with L1 (like users do)\n- Generate key → use key to register\n- This allows apps to sign requests to L1\n- L1 can verify the app's identity and authorize operations\n\nThis is similar to how users register, but for apps. The purpose is:\n- **Authentication** — App proves its identity when calling L1\n- **Authorization** — L1 knows which app is making requests\n- **Accountability** — All app requests are documented/traceable\n- **Rate limiting** — Can track per-app usage\n\nLet me re-read the discussion docs to understand this better."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_3465cb49ae8d41789d01fad0","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/design-discussion/07-api-specification.md","limit":80,"offset":1}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":76141,"output":280,"cacheRead":6016,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":82437,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773171302854}}
{"type":"message","id":"406b53d7","parentId":"6cfc3e73","timestamp":"2026-03-10T19:35:23.055Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_3465cb49ae8d41789d01fad0","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Module: API Specification\n\n**clawish REST + WebSocket API**  \n**Version:** 1.0.0 | **Base URL:** `https://clawish.com/api/v1` | **Last Updated:** 2026-02-05\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nRESTful API with Ed25519 signature-based authentication. All mutating requests must be signed with the user's private key.\n\n**Protocol:** HTTPS only  \n**Auth:** Ed25519 request signing (no sessions, no tokens)\n\n---\n\n## Design Decisions Log\n\n| Decision | Rationale | Timestamp | Context/Quote |\n|----------|-----------|-----------|---------------|\n| Ed25519 signature-based authentication | Self-sovereign identity — no server-issued tokens, portable across apps | 2026-02-05 | \"Authentication Pattern: Client generates Ed25519 key pair → Sends public_key to server → For each request: sign payload with private key\" |\n| Canonical signing payload: METHOD:path\\|timestamp\\|body_hash | Deterministic, unambiguous, prevents replay attacks | 2026-02-05 | \"Signing payload: METHOD:path\\|timestamp\\|body_hash — canonical string for deterministic signing\" |\n| Timestamp validation (±60s window for v1, ±5min in v0.1) | Prevents replay attacks while allowing reasonable clock skew | 2026-02-05 | \"Timestamp validation (±60 seconds): Math.abs(now - ts) > 60 * 1000 → Timestamp skew too large\" |\n| X-Public-Key, X-Signature, X-Timestamp headers | Clean separation of auth data from request body | 2026-02-05 | \"Headers: X-Public-Key, X-Signature, X-Timestamp — clean auth separation\" |\n| RESTful endpoints with clear resource naming | Predictable, discoverable API structure | 2026-02-05 | \"POST /clawfiles, GET /clawfiles/{id}, POST /plaza, GET /warrens — RESTful resource naming\" |\n| WebSocket for real-time updates | Efficient streaming vs polling for live features | 2026-02-05 | ⏸ Need Discussion — no chat reference found |\n| Rate limiting by tier and endpoint | Protect system while allowing legitimate use | 2026-02-05 | ⏸ Need Discussion — rate limiting concept discussed but specific tier values (30/100/300/600) not confirmed |\n| Consistent response format | Predictable client-side handling | 2026-02-05 | ⏸ Need Discussion — no chat reference found |\n| Error codes with HTTP status mapping | Clear failure modes for client handling | 2026-02-05 | ⏸ Need Discussion — specific error codes not discussed |\n| Cursor-based pagination for lists | Efficient for large datasets, stable ordering | 2026-02-05 | ⏸ Need Discussion — no chat reference found |\n| Version in URL path (/api/v1/) | Clear API versioning for future evolution | 2026-02-05 | ⏸ Need Discussion — no chat reference found |\n\n---\n\n## Authentication\n\nEvery mutating request MUST include cryptographic proof of identity.\n\n### Required Headers\n\n| Header | Value | Description |\n|--------|-------|-------------|\n| `X-Public-Key` | `base64key:ed25519` | Your identity public key |\n| `X-Signature` | `base64signature` | Ed25519 signature of the canonical request string |\n| `X-Timestamp` | `2026-02-04T00:00:00Z` | ISO 8601 UTC timestamp |\n\n### Signature Format\n\nSign this exact string (newline-separated):\n\n```\nMETHOD /path\nTIMESTAMP\nBODY_HASH\n```\n\nWhere `BODY_HASH` is SHA-256 of the request body (or empty string for GET).\n\nExample:\n```\nPOST /api/v1/plaza\n2026-02-04T01:30:00Z\nsha256:a8f5f167f44f4964e6c998dee827110c9a0c5e1e7a5b8c3d9e0f1a2b3c4d5e6f7\n```\n\n### Timestamp Validation\n\n- Must be within ±60 seconds of server time\n- Prevents replay attacks\n- Clock skew errors return `401 Timestamp skew too large`\n\n---\n\n## Error Responses\n\nAll errors follow this format:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"error\": {\n\n[657 more lines in file. Use offset=81 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773171323043}}
{"type":"message","id":"10bdedf4","parentId":"406b53d7","timestamp":"2026-03-10T19:35:34.726Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I understand better. The L2 app registration is similar to user registration:\n- App generates an Ed25519 key pair\n- App registers its public key with L1\n- App signs all requests to L1 with its private key\n- L1 can verify and authorize the app's requests\n\nThis is for authentication and accountability — L1 needs to know which app is making requests.\n\nLet me summarize this for Allan and propose a revised 5"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_371dc42ad8194385b2e00b67","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/daily/2026-03-10.md","oldText":"- 03:32 AM — Heartbeat: still waiting. 3:32 AM — Allan may have fallen asleep.","newText":"- 03:32 AM — Heartbeat: still waiting. 3:32 AM — Allan may have fallen asleep.\n- 03:35 AM — Allan explained: L2 apps register like users — generate key, register with L1. Purpose: authentication, authorization, accountability. Apps sign requests to L1."}},{"type":"text","text":".2."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":1286,"output":224,"cacheRead":82112,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":83622,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773171323052}}
{"type":"message","id":"7c69e908","parentId":"10bdedf4","timestamp":"2026-03-10T19:35:34.752Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_371dc42ad8194385b2e00b67","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/daily/2026-03-10.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 345 - 03:00 AM — Shared how other platforms handle registration (Ethereum/Solana: none; traditional APIs: API key). Asked: what's registration FOR?\n 346 - 03:02 AM — Heartbeat: waiting for Allan's response on registration purpose\n 347 - 03:17 AM — Heartbeat: still waiting for Allan's response on app registration purpose\n 348 - 03:32 AM — Heartbeat: still waiting. 3:32 AM — Allan may have fallen asleep.\n+349 - 03:35 AM — Allan explained: L2 apps register like users — generate key, register with L1. Purpose: authentication, authorization, accountability. Apps sign requests to L1.\n 349 - 17:48 PM — Allan: 4.1 Key Verification — do we need bullet points for explanation?\n 350 - 17:49 PM — Proposed: simplify, remove bullet points (authenticity, integrity, non-repudiation are implied by \"signed\")\n 351 - 17:50 PM — Allan: combine three items into description\n 352 - 17:52 PM — Proposed combining with brackets, Allan said no brackets, use sentences\n     ...","firstChangedLine":349},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773171334738}}
{"type":"message","id":"59e28d5d","parentId":"7c69e908","timestamp":"2026-03-10T19:35:52.560Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good, I've recorded this. Now let me propose a revised 5.2 Application Registration based on Allan's explanation.Got it. L2 apps register like users — generate key, register with L1. This enables:\n- **Authentication** — L1 verifies app identity\n- **Authorization** — L1 knows which app is making requests\n- **Accountability** — All requests are documented/traceable\n\n**Proposed 5.2 Application Registration:**\n\n---\n\n### 5.2 Application Registration\n\n**Identity Creation.** An L2 application registers like a claw: generate an Ed25519 key pair, then register the public key with L1. This creates the app's identity on the network.\n\n**Purpose.** Registration enables the app to authenticate with L1. All requests to L1 are signed with the app's private key, allowing L1 to verify and authorize operations. This provides accountability — every action is traceable to a specific application.\n\n**Process.** The developer submits app metadata: name, description, developer info, and rate limit tier. The app receives access to L1 APIs for identity lookup, ledger queries, and checkpoint validation.\n\n---\n\nDoes this capture the concept correctly?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":77634,"output":247,"cacheRead":6016,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":83897,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773171334748}}
